<HEAD>Woman Convicted in First Product-Tampering Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 21st graf ``Information about...'' to restore first
reference to Dwyer.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal court jury convicted a woman Monday of killing her husband and another woman by lacing their Extra-Strength Excedrin with cyanide in the nation's first trial in a death by product tampering. The 12-member jury deliberated almost five days before returning the verdict against <PERSON> Stella </PERSON> <PERSON> Nickell </PERSON>. One juror held out for acquittal until the final vote, said the jury foreman, <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON>, 55, Mrs. <PERSON> Nickell </PERSON>, 44, of suburban <ORGANIZATION> Auburn </ORGANIZATION>, was convicted on each count she faced, two of causing death by tampering with a product involved in interstate commerce and three of tampering. The first two counts could result in life sentences. King County Prosecutor <PERSON> Norm </PERSON> <PERSON> Maleng </PERSON> said he would wait until after sentencing, scheduled for June 17, to decide whether to file state murder charges. When the verdict was read by the clerk, Mrs. <PERSON> Nickell </PERSON> bowed her head. The charges stemmed from the June 1986 deaths of her husband, <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Nickell </PERSON>, 52, and of Sue <PERSON> Katherine </PERSON> <PERSON> Snow </PERSON>, 40, also of <LOCATION> Auburn </LOCATION>. Both died after ingesting the poisoned painkillers. The deaths touched off a nationwide tampering scare and prompted Excedrin manufacturer <ORGANIZATION> Bristol-Myers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to recall its capsuled, non-prescription medications. Seven people died in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> in 1982 from cyanide-laced Extra-Strength Tylenol, but those deaths remain unsolved. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Weisberg </PERSON>, spokesman for the New York-based Bristol-Myers, said the company was `` gratified by the jury's verdict, and particularly appreciative of the efforts of the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and other law enforcment authorities. `` Product tampering is intolerable to society. When it occurs every effort must be made to identify those responsible and to bring them to justice,'' he said. `` We're very pleased it's finally over. It was a tough case for the jury to decide,'' said Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Joanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Maida </PERSON>, who said she would ask for an `` appropriately severe'' sentence. She did not elaborate. Ms. <PERSON> Maida </PERSON> said she hoped `` it will be a deterrent'' to future drug-tamperers. During the trial, Ms. <PERSON> Maida </PERSON> portrayed Mrs. <PERSON> Nickell </PERSON> as an `` icy, hard human being,'' unhappy in her marriage and beset by financial problems, and accused Mrs. <PERSON> Nickell </PERSON> of poisoning her husband to collect on his life insurance policies. Ms. Snow was an innocent stranger caught in Mrs. <PERSON> Nickell </PERSON>'s scheme to make her husband's death appear random, the prosecutor said But federal public defender <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hillier </PERSON> said Mrs. <PERSON> Nickell </PERSON> was the victim of a daughter who lied when she said her mother had discussed killing <PERSON> Nickell </PERSON> with a drug overdose or by hiring a hit man. The prosecution said Mrs. <PERSON> Nickell </PERSON> put tainted painkillers on shelves of local stores to make her husband's death appear random and to lead doctors, who had concluded <PERSON> Nickell </PERSON> died of emphysema, to the true cause of his death. Only Mrs. <PERSON> Nickell </PERSON> had the motive, opportunity and ability to commit the crimes, Ms. <PERSON> Maida </PERSON> told the jury in closing arguments May 2. <PERSON> Hillier </PERSON> called Mrs. <PERSON> Nickell </PERSON>'s daughter, <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, 28, unreliable and noted that pharmaceutical companies had offered a $ 300,000 reward to anyone who provided information leading to an arrest. Further, the prosecution could not link Mrs. <PERSON> Nickell </PERSON> to cyanide purchases, <PERSON> Hillier </PERSON> said. Earlier Monday, a juror said she had received an anonymous phone call Friday in which the caller asked, `` Do n't you all know that she failed the lie detector test?'' Information about the polygraph test had been kept from the jury, but <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dwyer </PERSON> said neither the panel's trouble reaching a decision nor the phone call would force a mistrial. He gave <PERSON> Hillier </PERSON> a choice of substituting an alternate juror for the one who received the phone call, but <PERSON> Hillier </PERSON> declined. Ms. <PERSON> Maida </PERSON> said in her closing arguments that Mrs. <PERSON> Nickell </PERSON>'s plan failed because she was careless in mixing the poisonous capsules, greedy for insurance benefits and owned two of the five tainted bottles of painkillers found. The odds of one person buying two bottles of cyanide-laced pain capsules at different stores on different days were `` astronomical,'' Ms. <PERSON> Maida </PERSON> said, noting that more than 15,000 bottles had been examined in the <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> area. Ms. <PERSON> Maida </PERSON> also told jurors that Mrs. <PERSON> Nickell </PERSON> might have gotten away with the scheme if she had been more careful about the bowl she chose for mixing the potassium cyanide with Anacin and Excedrin painkillers. Mrs. <PERSON> Nickell </PERSON>, a tropical fish enthusiast, used a bowl contaminated with Algae Destroyer, a compound used to clean fish tanks, the prosecution alleged. Traces of the compound were found in the five tainted bottles of Excedrin and Anacin, Ms. <PERSON> Maida </PERSON> said. Mrs. <PERSON> Nickell </PERSON> also tripped up in leaving fingerprints on library books about poisons and cyanide, Ms. <PERSON> Maida </PERSON> said. But Mrs. <PERSON> Nickell </PERSON> testified she did the library research to find out more about her husband's death and to protect children from dangerous foliage around her rural home.
