<HEAD>Justice Department Eyes Way Cities Test Police Candidates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is reviewing a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> literacy test for would-be law enforcement officers that is failed by three out of four blacks and two out of three Hispanics. The federal inquiry is intended to determine whether the test discriminates against minorities seeking jobs in nearly 300 <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> law enforcement agencies. Minority groups tend to be underrepresented in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> law enforcement, and critics say hiring practices may contribute to the prevalence of white faces in blue uniforms. If the department concludes that the test is discriminatory, `` we'd have to take appropriate steps to address that problem,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Burstion-Wade </PERSON>. The test indicates whether a job candidate reads and writes at high-school level, skills presumed necessary if the candidate is to understand the laws being enforced. One section requires the person to complete a sentence by picking the correctly spelled word from three choices. Other sections test grammar. Another section asks the test taker to choose the clearest of three sentences discussing the same topic. The wrong answers contain `` extremely basic, obvious ambiguities,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Boatright </PERSON>, an attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> Officer Standards and Education. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has looked at numerous other state, city or county writing or reading tests for their effect on minorities, and employment criteria for physical strength and agility and their effect on women. Exams reviewed by the agency have ranged from the <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, county police test to the <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> toll facilities police force's height and weight restrictions. In <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, during the past 7 -LCB- months, passing rates were 69 percent for whites; 67 percent for <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION>; 59 percent for Asian-Americans; 36 percent for Hispanics; and 27 percent for blacks. Overall, 55 percent of the people who took the test between Sept. 1, 1987, and April 21 passed it, according to the law enforcement standards commission. People who fail may repeat the exam. As of Feb. 17, the state had 41,916 licensed law enforcement officers, 7.3 percent of whom were black, according to the most recent figures from the commission. Figures from the 1980 census show 12 percent of Texans are black. The commission had the test developed in the mid-1970s and used <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> criteria in drafting it. `` We offered to run it by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> and they refused,'' said attorney <PERSON> Boatright </PERSON>. `` We're perfectly happy that they're looking at it now.'' One of the 283 law enforcement agencies using the test is <LOCATION> Lufkin </LOCATION>. Police Chief <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> says he does n't fault the exam for the absence of black officers on his force, although blacks make up about one-fourth of the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> town's population of 30,000. <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> says basic literacy is essential for an officer, and to help prepare candidates he has enlisted the help of an adult learning center which offers preparation for the high school General Equivalency Diploma exam. The local agency is offering a six-week course to raise reading comprehension and writing skills up to five grade levels, <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. `` We want black officers,'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. `` We would have a better rapport with the black community if we had black officers out there serving them.'' Only one black out of 13 passed the test in <LOCATION> Lufkin </LOCATION> in June, when it was offered last. The person who passed was a reporter who took the exam as part of a news assignment for the <ORGANIZATION> Lufkin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>.
