<HEAD>The Election's Not Over, But There Were Clear Winners and Losers
Among Ads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Only a handful of television viewers witnessed one of the best ads of the 1988 presidential campaign _ 10 seconds of <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Haig </PERSON> stuffing pizza into his mouth at a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> eatery. `` It got on the air one day before he withdrew,'' said <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>, <PERSON> Haig </PERSON>'s media consultant. The ad showed a mischievous-looking <PERSON> Haig </PERSON> using his fingers to subdue some errant pizza cheese, and instantly turned the off-putting general into a likable human being. Political media observers, from academics to admakers, say few if any TV spots this year have broken new technical ground or connected emotionally with voters. Among the notable exceptions was Democrat <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s `` $ 48,000 <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION>'' spot _ a trade tirade aimed at Korean tariffs that price <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> autos out of the Korean market `` The populist impulses in the <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> ad, the defiant expression, identified with the electorate's feeling of powerlessness,'' said <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> <PERSON> Jamieson </PERSON>, a professor and author of two books on political ads and speeches. `` It was a moment of empowerment. It let the voters feel good.'' <PERSON> Jamieson </PERSON> also nominated the pizza ad, saying it forced the viewer to reconsider <PERSON> Haig </PERSON>'s somewhat negative and militaristic image. The clear message was that `` if you knew him, you'd like him,'' she said. The short spot shows <PERSON> Haig </PERSON> with a piece of cheese hanging between his mouth and his pizza slice. He pulls it up to his mouth with his finger, realizes he's on-camera, and winks. Meanwhile, a narrator is saying with mock seriousness, `` Former Secretary of State <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Haig </PER