<HEAD>Dukakis Braces For Bush Attacks On Crime Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 During last year's legislative session, <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bulger </PERSON> relegated a capital-punishment bill to committee, effectively killing it. <PERSON> Bulger </PERSON> supports the death penalty. But he also supports <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> _ and his move spared the governor from having to veto a death-penalty bill. The incident illustrated how carefully the Democratic presidential front-runner is treading when it comes to crime and punishment. But Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has already attacked <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> on some crime issues, and made it clear that there's more criticism to come. At a news conference in <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> last week, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> faulted both <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and Democrat <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> for not supporting the death penalty for `` drug kingpins.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> opposes the death penalty under all circumstances. Another potential point of vulnerability is the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> prison system, one of the most overcrowded in the country. With 6,600 inmates, it is 72 percent over capacity. The legislature, pushed by <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, allocated nearly $ 1 billion to expand capacity, but it will take years to ease the overcrowding. And <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> ran into a storm of protest last year when <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Horton </PERSON>, a convicted murderer, walked away from a weekend furlough. He was arrested later in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> and convicted of raping a woman and beating her husband. The <PERSON> Horton </PERSON> case prompted angry calls for elimination of furloughs for first-degree murderers serving life sentences. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> defended the furlough program for months, on grounds that it h