<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Readers of <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>'s book, `` For the Record,'' might be confused by lack of quotation remarks around most of the quotations from President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. In reporting his conversations with the president, the former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> chief of staff consistently put his own words inside quote marks, but leaves them out in reporting the president's remarks Thus, a typical passage reads: Hi, <PERSON> Don </PERSON>, the President said. Is this a good time to talk? I said, `` Could n't be better, Mr. President.'' <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> explains it this way; `` Out of deference to the office and the man, I have not enclosed language attributed to the president in quotation marks except in cases where his words have already appeared in print elsewhere.''
