<HEAD>Jackson Challenge Of Delegate Seating Likely, Campaign Chairman
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> will probably challenge the seating of delegates at the Democratic convention in July because it appears party officials will not act on his objections to the selection process, his campaign chairman says. <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, speaker of the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, said he and other <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> advisers have spoken to <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> and other party leaders about <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s insistence that the delegate totals roughly correspond to the popular vote But those talks, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said, are `` not so far productive,'' and the campaign will likely make challenges to the delegate slates of states where it believes the selection has been unfair. `` I think we are going to end up having to make them because I do n't think it's -LRB- the discussion -RRB- going to be productive,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Saturday. In recent days, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has said he is appealing to party leaders for `` some measure of fairness,'' but he has shied away from any indication that he would make an official challenge or employ the kind of attack he made in disputing party rules in 1984. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> uses <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> as an example _ in that contest, he won the popular vote but the governor awarded all of the island's delegates to <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> Party rules allow for such practices, although in many states the delegate allocation is tied directly to the popular vote. A successful challenge could narrow the gap of roughly 600 delegates between <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and make the delegate tallies more closely reflect the popular vote, which currently stands at some 37 percent for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> to 28 percent for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. `` If we can mount some credential challenge on fairness, this thing does n't have to be over,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said when asked about the conclusion by some observers that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> all but has the nomination locked up. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has said he will talk with `` super delegates'' from congressional districts where he won the popular vote, and appeal for their support even though they are not bound to follow the vote totals. Super delegates attend the convention by virtue of their position as public or party officeholders. On Sunday, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> took that a step further, saying that white Democratic officeholders, especially those in the South who have benefited from the black vote, should be willing to support him on that basis. He singled out <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON> and former <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, who angered <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> supporters by endorsing <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> Jr.. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> narrowly defeated <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> primary `` It's reasonable to expect that Sen. <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON> will endorse my campaign. That's a reasonable expectation,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, noting that the black vote was crucial to <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON>'s 1986 election. <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON> is a super delegate. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has also hinted that his supporters might stay away from the polls in November if they perceived he was being treated unfairly. He indirectly raised the possibility again on Sunday. `` We define our friends by their willingness to be fair and to be just,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. `` One thing about politics, it does not go up and down. It goes round and round. Anything that goes around comes around.'' Regardless of the outcome of the race for the nomination, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> officials are confident their delegate strength will ensure their influence on the party platform, and are working on what issues they want to include. `` We wo n't have to worry about getting every plank we want considered,'' said <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>. In the meantime, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is unveiling the themes that he hopes will increase that strength in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, the nation's biggest delegate prize. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has an active and broad organization of supporters but he, like <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, must figure out how to appeal to the wider population in this state of 25 million that appears to lack enthusiasm for this year's election. Most Democratic officeholders so far are sitting out the campaign, apparently reluctant to endorse either <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> or <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. Many of them had earlier endorsed one of the five Democrats who have since dropped out of the race. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> characterized his non-endorsing colleagues in the state legislature and other neutral politicians as mostly `` mainstream traditional Democrats'' who would not be expected to endorse the liberal <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and who do n't feel they know enough about <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has been targeting women, environmentalists, Hispanics, gays and peace activists, and continuing to sound his anti-drug and anti-Reaganomics themes. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said campaign strategists are to meet this week to determine what kind of television commercials will be aired in what campaign manager <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> said will be about a $ 2 million ad campaign. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> `` is a hotbed for peace'' and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s positions on peace in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> should sell well, especially on the state's more than 140 college campuses, said <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>.
