<FIRST>r p PM-Jackson-BlackVote     05-09 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jackson-Black Vote,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unlike '84, Black Share of the Primary Vote is Level in Many
States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Although <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has been dramatically successful in the Democratic primaries this year, analysts say he has not repeated a major accomplishment of his 1984 presidential campaign: expanding the black share of the vote. Four years ago, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> drew a vastly higher black turnout in many states. Blacks made up a fifth of the Democratic electorate in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, up from 8 percent in 1980; a sixth in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, also up from 8 percent. But while he has drawn enthusiastic crowds, expanded his support among whites and raised his own share of the black vote this time around, he has not galvanized more blacks to register and vote. `` His first candidacy brought a lot more black voters to the polls. There was a clear pattern of increased black participation,'' said <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> poll analyst <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>. `` That pattern is not repeating itself this year.'' Black voter turnout is crucial for the Democrats because blacks make up one of their core voting blocs. Strategists say <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> could boost the Democrats' chances if he could deliver an expanded black vote in the general election _ and hurt the party's odds if he should discourage black support of the ticket. Viewing the primary results so far, `` The major implication is that you can not expect an unusual black turnout this year,'' said independent pollster <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>. `` If the Democrats are counting on a disproportionate black turnout, it seems to be it's going to be difficult to achieve,'' <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said. `` If <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> ca n't achieve it when there's a direct one-to-one relationship, it's more unlikely to happen when it's not a one-to-one relationship.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> increased black voting in 1984 through massive voter registration drives. He has not conducted such intensive drives this year, and exit polls in many states have found the black vote virtually unchanged from 1984 as a share of the electorate. <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> polls said blacks made up 19 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> voters in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> last month, compared to 20 percent in 1984; in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, 16 percent this year, 17 percent in 1984; in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, 24 percent this year, 24 percent in 1984. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> poll results have been similar. `` In <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, despite the publicity about the crowds that greeted <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, black turnout actually was down a bit from 1984,'' said <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>. `` It was steady in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, steady in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, down a bit in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, up a bit in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.'' Polls have shown sizable increases in some states: In <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, blacks made up 35 percent of the turnout in the <ORGANIZATION> CBS-Times </ORGANIZATION> poll, up from 28 percent in 1984. In <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, though, an <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> poll said blacks made up 32 percent in 1988, little changed from 30 percent in 1984. In many cases, more blacks may have voted this year than in 1984, but not in numbers any greater than the increase of other voters, pollsters noted. Another issue for Democrats is whether black turnout may fluctuate in the general election as it has in the primaries, or is more likely to remain stable. In 1984, some analysts expected a greater share of blacks, newly energized by <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, to vote Democratic in November, <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said. But blacks made up 8 percent of the general election vote, down a point from 1980 and three points below their share of the voting age population. The 1984 general election may be a poor example, pollster <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said, `` because that was n't a fight that was turning a lot of people on.'' Still, he said he was surprised that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has not broadly boosted black voters' electoral share this year. `` It just lets you know institutionally how difficult it is,'' <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said. `` Even one man as good as he is is n't able to disproportionately shift the electorate.''
</TEXT>
