<HEAD>Ecuadoreans Elect Left-Leaning President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Rodrigo </PERSON> <PERSON> Borja </PERSON>, a center-left lawyer who promised to distance his administration from the current government's pro-U.S. foreign policy, was elected president of <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Borja </PERSON>, 52, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Left </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, defeated populist <PERSON> Abdala </PERSON> <PERSON> Bucaram </PERSON>, 36, in an runoff on Sunday to select a successor to conservative <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s closest ally in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. With the vote count virtually complete, <PERSON> Borja </PERSON> had 1,631,747 votes to <PERSON> Bucaram </PERSON>'s 1,401,153 votes. Nearly 450,000 votes were blank or nullified. More than 4.6 million Ecuadoreans were registered to vote. <PERSON> Bucaram </PERSON>, speaking on national television from his power base in <LOCATION> Guayaquil </LOCATION>, the country's largest city and its major port, conceded defeat Sunday night and congratulated <PERSON> Borja </PERSON>. `` There are no excuses. Dr. <PERSON> Rodrigo </PERSON> <PERSON> Borja </PERSON> is the president of <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Bucaram </PERSON>, a fiery campaigner who had sworn to `` punish the oligarchy'' if elected. Speaking over television in <LOCATION> Quito </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Borja </PERSON> said, `` Thank you, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, thank you.'' It was <PERSON> Borja </PERSON>'s third bid for the presidency. He was narrowly defeated by <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON> in a bitterly fought runoff in 1984 and has pledged to reverse his foe's free-market economic policies. But he also told <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>'s business community not to be frightened by his election. `` Our victory should not make anyone nervous. No one should set off a financial panic,'' <PERSON> Borja </PERSON> said Sunday night. `` We intend to respect private enterprise.'' <PERSON> Borja </PERSON> has promised to back a moratorium on payment of <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>'s $ 9.2 billion dollar foreign debt if creditors do n't agree to negotiate easier terms `` I do not believe it is possible to pay the foreign debt under the conditions they want to collect,'' he said in a recent meeting with foreign correspondents. `` Either we pay the debt or we develop the country. We ca n't do both things at the same time.'' The <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON> government suspended payment on the debt last year after severe economic damage from devastating earthquakes. <PERSON> Borja </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bucaram </PERSON> defeated eight other candidates in the first round of elections Jan. 31 to qualify for the runoff. <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, came in third, a sign of his government's low popularity. The victory by the left-leaning <PERSON> Borja </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bucaram </PERSON> sent tremors through <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>'s financial circles. The Ecuadorean currency plunged in value from 275 sucres to the dollar to nearly 500 sucres since the first round of voting. <PERSON> Borja </PERSON> has said he plans to establish exchange controls and restrict imports to protect <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>'s dangerously low dollar reserves. He also plans price controls on basic consumer goods. He says he will seek close ties to the non-aligned movement and re-establish diplomatic relations with leftist-led <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON> severed relations in 1985 after an argument with Nicaraguan President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>. <PERSON> Borja </PERSON> will be sworn in Aug. 10 for a four-year term. He will be the third elected president since democracy was restored in 1979 after nine years of civilian and military dictatorships. <PERSON> Borja </PERSON> will confront the challenge of a governing a nation that is in its deepest recession since it began exporting oil in the early 1970s. The economy shrank 3.5 percent last year, thanks in great measure to the sharp drop in the price of oil, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>'s major source of income. Inflation is running at an annual rate of 70 percent, the highest level since 1983, and less than half the work force has full-time employment.
