<HEAD>U.S.-Soviet Cartoon Exchange Paints Picture Of Rosy Glasnost</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Wiley in 11th graf cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet artists are trying to draw the cultural gap between the two countries to a close, and the idea has people laughing. The traveling `` USSR-USA Cartoon Exchange'' features cartoons from both countries that sponsors hope will erase walls of misunderstanding. Is it working? `` Da!'' exclaimed the show's curator, <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Swenson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. `` Big yes! `` Cartoons communicate the universal, wordless art that can make people laugh,'' he said during the show's debut here this weekend. `` I'm overwhelmed by the instant rapport the artists from the two countries develop. Listen to the sound in this building.'' The sound Saturday in the gallery was laughter. Through a live `` videophone'' hook-up, about 10 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> artists serenaded a group of Soviet artists in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. They requested `` a typical American song'' and got `` Take Me Out to the <LOCATION> Ball </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>.'' The Americans got a long-distance ovation. `` I'm literally blown away by the quality and the humor,'' said <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Bassett </PERSON>, editorial cartoonist for the <ORGANIZATION> Seattle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> who draws the syndicated comic strip `` Adam.'' `` I guess that's an indication of how little our two cultures have touched,'' he said. <PERSON> Iuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Ivanov </PERSON>, a 41-year-old cartoonist from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on hand for the opening, picked his favorite American exhibit of the 40 being shown and sent it electronically to his colleagues in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. `` I like it because it's stupid,'' <PERSON> Ivanov </PERSON> said, not being critical. `` It describes the stupidity of the situation perfectly.'' The cartoon by <PERSON> Wiley </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> showed a complacent Soviet Bear and casual Uncle <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> standing in front of two television cameras, one camera Soviet, the other Amercian. The lens in the American camera shows the bear trying to devour Uncle <PERSON> Sam </PERSON>. Conversely, the lens in the Soviet camera shows Uncle <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> with a gun to the bear's head. `` Very definately the perceptions are changing,'' <PERSON> Ivanov </PERSON> said. `` The more of these type of exchanges, the more this picture wo n't be true. Not even the most optimistic of the 50 or so people at the opening saw rosy Soviet-U.S. relations being painted with one stroke of the brush. <PERSON> Ivanov </PERSON>, however, hailed increased cultural exchanges made possible by Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of glasnost, which has opened doors for Soviet artists. The few political jabs in the cartoons shown by the Soviet artists were light, and any political satire tended to generalize. Bureaucracy was lampooned, not the bureaucrats. In one of <PERSON> Ivanov </PERSON>'s watercolors, a man tied to a noose serves as the clapper in a bell. A smiling man in a uniform swings from the hapless clapper's feet. `` The common man suffers so others can enjoy,'' <PERSON> Ivanov </PERSON> explained. But he quickly pointed out the picture is n't representative of capitalism or communism `` It's like that everywhere,'' he said. Some Americans are slow to accept glasnost as anything more than a concept, he said. For instance, he pointed to a picture by <PERSON> Milt </PERSON> <PERSON> Prigee </PERSON>, editorial cartoonist for the <ORGANIZATION> Spokane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Spokesman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION>. The cartoon shows a man behind bars, with the familiar smiley faces drawn around it along with the Soviet sickle and the word `` glasnost.'' `` The artist does n't understand the situation of glasnost,'' <PERSON> Ivanov </PERSON> said. `` The bars are cut. That was a problem before, but not anymore. Things are immensely better under <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>.'' Asked for an example, <PERSON> Ivanov </PERSON> replied, `` For example, I am here.'' The show continues here through June 7 before heading to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>. After that it moves to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>
