<SECOND>PM-Bad Writing,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>It Was A Dark And Stormy Paragraph</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 What makes a good sentence go bad? `` Like an expensive sports car, fine-tuned and well-built, <PERSON> Portia </PERSON> was sleek, shapely and gorgeous, her red jumpsuit moulding her body, which was as warm as the seatcovers in July, her hair as dark as new tires, her eyes flashing like bright hubcaps, and her lips dewy as the beads of fresh rain on the hood; she was a woman driven _ fueled by a single accelerant _ and she needed a man, a man who would n't shift from his views, a man to steer her along the right road: a man like <PERSON> Alf </PERSON> <PERSON> Romeo </PERSON>.'' That awful thing was submitted to the annual Bulwer-Lytton Fiction Contest by 20-year-old journalism student <PERSON> Rachel </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheeley </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Franklin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. It brought her to the top _ or the bottom _ of the heap of more than 11,000 entries. The top honor _ or, again, the lack of it _ was announced Sunday by <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jose </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> Professor <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, founder and `` grand panjandrum'' of the literary disgrace he calls `` the <ORGANIZATION> Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orioles </ORGANIZATION> of literature.'' Whether a boon or bane for the winner's career, <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> points out that the competition is not a joke-writing contest. `` It really takes a very good writer to deliberately write bad,'' he said. The contest trashes the battered memory of 19th century English writer <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Earle </PERSON> <PERSON> Bulwer-Lytton </PERSON>, whose turgid style is captured in the opening line of one of his novels: `` It was a dark and stormy night. ...'' <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> notes that <PERSON> Bulwer-Lytton </PERSON> also is remembered for such ringing cliches as `` The pen is mightier than the sword'' and `` The Great Unwashed.'' The contest also is a gentle reminder to the world of letters that it is OK to lighten up, forget the grammar books for a minute and have some fun, to `` approach the language recreationally as well as practically,'' <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> said. For her effort, <ORGANIZATION> Sheeley </ORGANIZATION> wins a word processor. This, <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> noted, illustrates the computer-terminology adage, `` Garbage in, garbage out.'' Awards also were made in selected categories. <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION> won in puns: `` Once a month, when the moon is full, Reverend <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Bleaker </PERSON> and his lovely wife <PERSON> Teddi </PERSON> invite members of the church to the parsonage for an evening of hymn singing, followed by cookies, tea, and a frenzied orgy on the lawn outside, making sure, of course, to take all the usual precautions for safe sects.'' <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazulelwicz </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Liverpool </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, won for purple prose: `` The silent snow fell relentlessly, unceasingly, mercilessly from the sordid, sullied surreality of the sky as if some enormous, ethereal diner were shaking grated parmesan on the great, soggy meatball that was earth.'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Stratford </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Miles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mont. </LOCATION>, won for science fiction: `` <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> doubted that her alien escort, composed as he was of vegetable matter, seaweed, and a thick coating of swampy muck, would be a suitable date for the Intergalactic kegger, but he turned out to be a real FUNGI.'' R.B. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Nottinghamshire </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, won for detective novel: `` With the radio squawking that a 4711 was in progress at 37th and 127th, <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> knocked car 495 into 3rd and headed up 5th at 70, little reckoning, as he thumbed his .38, that this would be the day when his number came up.''
