<HEAD>U.S. Navy Explodes Mine In Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The following dispatch is from <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kearns </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION>, the press representative in the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> news pool in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. ABOARD THE USS COPELAND -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> divers have exploded a mine found drifting in the northern <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> by the missile frigate <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON>. The mine found Sunday was the first discovered in the area since the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> missile frigate <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> was nearly sunk by a mine last month. Also Sunday, three motor boats raced toward a convoy of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ships, but veered off. A <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> official said they were probably operated by smugglers. Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyke </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, told a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> media pool the <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> reported the mine was 85 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Farsi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, where the <LOCATION> Iranians </LOCATION> have a military base. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> divers detonated it an hour later. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyke </PERSON> said the mine was an encrusted Myam-type mine that apparently had broken loose from its mooring. The Myam is smaller than the type of mine containing 250 pounds of explosives that holed the <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> on April 14 off <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION>, 140 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Farsi </LOCATION>, wounding 10 crewmen. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has accused <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> of laying the mines to disrupt gulf shipping. In retaliation for the <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> mining, he ordered attacks on Iranian oil platforms April 18. That led to a string of clashes between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Iranian ships. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> claimed it sunk three Iranian warships and damaged three others. A multi-national mine sweeping force has detonated at least six mines since the <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> was hit. French warships have reported finding other mines further south in that period. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, backed by the British, French, Belgians and Italians, has dealt with scores of mines in or near the gulf since last summer. Sunday's mine discovery came as shipping traffic picked up in the waterway after a lull caused by last month's clashes. But the shipping community remains edgy. <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> has sworn revenge for its losses last month. Earlier Sunday, three fast-moving motor boats raced across the <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION>, gateway to the gulf, toward a U.S.-escorted convoy. One darted under the Copeland's guns across the warship's bow. That jarred already jittery nerves aboard the convoy ships as the whaler-type boat sped past into the wake of the supply ship USS San Jose and the oil tanker Ranger. All three unidentified boats then disappeared into the sweltering haze, heading toward the <LOCATION> Oman </LOCATION> coast. The <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON>'s captain, Cmdr. G.M. <PERSON> Ziller </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, radioed a warning to the apparently unarmed boats, but raised no response. <PERSON> Ziller </PERSON> said they may have been smugglers who decided to ignore what he joked was the `` law of gross tonnage'' by zipping in front of the heavily armed 3,600-ton frigate. `` I do n't think there was any hostile intent,'' he said. The convoy passed within range of Chinese-made Silkworm missiles on the nearby Iranian coast. The pace of U.S.-escorted convoys has returned to what it was before the April 18 fighting and <LOCATION> Iranian </LOCATION> navy ships have all but disappeared. Four convoys have moved through the strait in the past week and <ORGANIZATION> navy </ORGANIZATION> officials say the escort operations will continue as needed. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s 354-foot supply ship, <PERSON> Booshehr </PERSON>, glided within 2,500 yards of the 3,700-ton missile frigate USS Jack Williams early Saturday. The two ships sailed past each other without incident in the the closest encounter between the two navies since last month's battles. Some <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officers believe the Iranians are licking their wounds and deciding what went wrong before making the next move. `` I think they're doing what we would be doing in the same situation,'' the skipper of the 24,000-ton <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, Capt. <PERSON> Willard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Halley </PERSON>, told the media pool Saturday. `` They're figuring out what happened to the chain of command and who's responsible and what should be done about it. `` This could be a lull while they work on the next step,'' he said, noting a long-standing split between the regular Iranian <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and the Revolutionary Guards who have attacked neutral shipping with armed speedboats. Since the April 18 fighting, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has laid down new rules for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships patrolling the gulf, allowing them to help non-American ships under attack if <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intervention is requested. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has 28 warships in the region, including an aircraft carrier-led task force stationed in the north <LOCATION> Arabian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>.
