<FIRST>r a PM-SchoolExperiment     05-09 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-School Experiment,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teachers, Administrators Poised to Approve Power-Sharing Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EASTON, PA. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A small school district plans to embark on an experiment that will give teachers greater authority but also greater accountability for producing well-educated children. If approved tonight by the school board and the eastern <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> district's 400 teachers, the three-year contract extension will give teachers a greater voice in student discipline and promotion, budgets and school board meetings. If the teachers' new roles do not improve student performance, the plan and most of the gains teachers stand to make will end with the contract extension, said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Moloney </PERSON>, superintendent of the <ORGANIZATION> Easton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION>. `` If we find out that dictatorial governance works better, then by <PERSON> God </PERSON>, we'll do it,'' <PERSON> Moloney </PERSON> said. `` But we believe that's not true.'' The idea, called `` shared governance,'' also calls for creation of a labor-management panel to hear concerns about teacher transfers, assignments or schedule changes, and a master teacher panel to recognize superior teachers and to encourage them to assist colleagues falling short of expectations. `` Shared governance says, ` You are a professional and we're now going to give you control over what you are entrusted to do,'' said <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON>, a fifth-grade teacher and president-elect of the teachers' union. The plan was proposed by <PERSON> Moloney </PERSON> and revised during eight months of discussion with principals, teachers, union representatives and school board members. The contract extension includes significant increases in teachers' and principals' salaries beginning in 1990, <PERSON> Moloney </PERSON> said. The average teacher salary in the district is about $ 28,400, but the parties refused to provide specific figures on increases before the vote. Known as an advocate for teachers, <PERSON> Moloney </PERSON> gained their trust soon after arriving here in late 1984. In 1985, he won approval of a five-year contract in a district where bitterness led to strikes in 1976 and 1980. <PERSON> Moloney </PERSON> said much of the proposal was based on his interpretations of recommendations made in the May 1986 <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> task force report called ` A Nation Prepared: Teachers for the 21st Century.'' Some of its recommendations have been tried in <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Moloney </PERSON> was assistant superintendent before coming to <LOCATION> Easton </LOCATION>. Large salaries for teachers and limited shared governance have made <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION> a much-scrutinized laboratory for school reform, but <PERSON> Moloney </PERSON> wanted to go further. The <PERSON> Easton </PERSON> proposal differs by forcing teachers and principals to bet major contract provisions on plans scheduled to take effect two years later. All participants _ the school board, teachers and principals _ can veto the plans, which include a new evaluation system for teachers and administrators and a new program to recognize outstanding teachers. If any provision fails to take effect as scheduled, the principals forfeit their hefty salary increases and the teachers lose their personnel committee for reviewing teacher transfers. `` This is serious carrot and stick stuff,'' <PERSON> Moloney </PERSON> said. The pact is part of <PERSON> Moloney </PERSON>'s larger goal _ teaching the district's 7,600 students to read and write, add and subtract. <PERSON> Moloney </PERSON> said his plan will mean nothing if it does not produce better-educated children. `` The bottom line is demonstrably improved outcome,'' <PERSON> Moloney </PERSON> said. `` The name of the game in education reform is better outcomes.''
</TEXT>
