<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar was mixed in moderate European trading early today, but traders predicted it would strengthen on speculation the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> will raise interest rates. Gold prices rose. One foreign currency dealer in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, said Friday's figures showing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unemployment rate was 5.4 percent in April, the lowest level in 14 years, has strengthened fears the American economy is overheating `` The unemployment figure sparked fears of renewed inflation, forcing the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> to act soon,'' to raise interest rates, she said. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends as <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar slipped 0.01 yen to a closing 124.87. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 124.85 yen. Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday: _ 1.6815 West German marks, up from 1.6805 _ 1.4000 Swiss francs, down from 1.4015 _ 5.7155 French francs, down from 5.7230 _ 1.8870 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8860 _ 1,252.40 Italian lire, down from 1,254.00 _ 1.2365 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2375 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one British pound cost $ 1.8760, more expensive for buyers than Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 443.25 a troy ounce, up from late Friday's $ 442.10. It was little changed in quiet trading at midmorning when the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 443.60. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 443.45, up from $ 443 late Friday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose 79 cents to close at a bid $ 446.66. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 6.37 a troy ounce, up marginally from Friday's $ 6.36.
