<HEAD>Ambassador Denies Briefing Bush On Noriega Drug Deals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto NY15</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> denied telling Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as early as 1985 that Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> may have been involved in drug trafficking. The ambassador, <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> <PERSON> Briggs </PERSON>, said on Sunday there was not enough evidence against <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s de facto ruler, at that time. `` I could not have briefed the vice president on <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s drug-running, drug-smuggling or money-laundering activities because we simply did not have evidence of those activities at that time and so any statement to the effect that I did brief him on such matters at that time simply is not true,'' <PERSON> Briggs </PERSON> told a news conference in <LOCATION> Tegucigalpa </LOCATION> The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported in its Sunday editions that <PERSON> Briggs </PERSON> had sent cables to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> about allegations of <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s drug dealings, and that <PERSON> Briggs </PERSON> told <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> about the substance of those cables during a meeting on Dec. 16, 1985. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, a Republican presidential candidate, has said he knew of no clear evidence that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> was involved in drugs until February. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> commands <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s Defense Forces and is the power behind the civilian government in that nation. The general was indicted by two federal grand juries in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> on drug trafficking charges and has rejected <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> demands that he resign. <PERSON> Briggs </PERSON> was ambassador to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> in 1985 and is now ambassador to <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. He acknowledged that there were persistent reports about <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> and drug trafficking. `` Panamanian sources would come to us and say ` Why do you have dealings with this man when it is well known that he is a drug smuggler?' and our answer always was ` Provide us the evidence,' and unfortunately during the time I was in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> that evidence was not forthcoming,'' he said. `` Now I am sorry it took so long for us to get the evidence,'' he said. `` I am sorry that we were n't able to get it sooner and I am very, very glad that the evidence was available finally so that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> could be indicted. I consider him probably the most pernicious element in this hemisphere at this time.'' A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Tegucigalpa </LOCATION> read a partial transcript of <PERSON> Briggs </PERSON>' news conference statements to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, quoting unidentified <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration officials, reported that a memo from <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aides to the vice president before his meeting with <PERSON> Briggs </PERSON> said the meeting was to `` discuss <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> relations with <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and narcotics matters.'' <PERSON> Briggs </PERSON> said he did not have a written record of what he and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> discussed during their meeting, but he imagined it would have been the slaying of <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Spadafora </PERSON>, a critic of <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, and the circumstances leading to <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s ouster of elected President <PERSON> Nicolas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ardito </PERSON> <PERSON> Barletta </PERSON>. He said he doubted he would have discussed with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> the cables he was sending to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> at the time.
