<HEAD>Scattered Violence In New Caledonia On France's Election Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-France-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL DONNET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In scattered violence during the French presidential election, a bus driver was shot and wounded while driving people to the polls and police dispersed Melanesian separatists blocking a street. In another development, authorities said funerals were held peacefully on Sunday on the island of <LOCATION> Ouvea </LOCATION> in this French <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> territory for Melanesian separatist kidnappers killed when police freed their hostages. In <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, the main Melanesian separatist group, the <ORGANIZATION> Kanak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, hailed the re-election of President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> on Sunday. <PERSON> Djim </PERSON> <PERSON> Ouenei </PERSON>, the group's representative, said the <LOCATION> Kanak </LOCATION> people, as native Melanesians are known, were renewing their proposal to negotiate `` to get out of this colonialist mess. Conservative Premier <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> won a record number of votes in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION>, 90.3 percent, while Socialist <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> took the rest. But in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> roundly defeated <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>. Native Melanesians make up 43 percent of the inhabitants of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION>, colonized by <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in 1853. Thirty-six percent are of European descent and the others are Asians and Polynesians. Many Melanesians want independence, but but a majority of the Europeans and others wish to remain part of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. Police in the capital of <LOCATION> Noumea </LOCATION> said the bus driver was hit in the legs by buckshot Sunday afternoon as he drove 15 Melanesians to a polling station in <LOCATION> Pouembout </LOCATION>, on the west coast of the main island and 150 miles north of <LOCATION> Noumea </LOCATION>. No other injuries were reported. In the town of <PERSON> Yate </PERSON> on the south end of the main island, police used tear gas to disperse a crowd of separatists who erected a barricade. The French High Commissioner reported that 14 of 128 polling stations were moved `` for reasons of public order.'' Voter turnout on the archipelego was 61.69 percent, up from 59 percent in the first round of balloting two weeks ago in which <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> also took the lion's share of the votes. The conservative Rally for the Republic in <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION>, a local spinoff of <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>'s Rally for the Republic party, controls the regional government. Separatists boycotted and attempted to disrupt the first round on April 24, but promised last week not to take similar action this time. On April 22, separatists stormed a police station on the island of <LOCATION> Ouvea </LOCATION>, northeast of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION>'s main island, killed four gendarmes and abducted others. A second group of gendarmes was abducted several days later. On Thursday, police stormed the cave where the 23 hostages were being held and killed 19 of the kidnappers. Two members of the French military assault team also were killed and five people were wounded.
