<HEAD>Nervous NATO Watches Danish Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUNILLA FARINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Danes </PERSON> vote in a parliamentary election Tuesday that will serve as a referendum on this nation's future in the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> alliance Prime Minister <PERSON> Poul </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> called for the elections just eight months after the last vote because the socialist-dominated parliament ignored his objections and passed a resolution toughening <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s non-nuclear status. Under parliament's resolution, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> must notify each visiting warship that nuclear arms are barred from Danish ports in peacetime. That has been the Danish stand for 31 years, but until now it has been merely a general statement of policy. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> said such a resolution would undermine the unity of the Western alliance and could threaten the ability of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> to protect <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> in an emergency. <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON>, leader of the minority center-right government, called for new elections rather than implement the resolution. The opposition campaign has taken on an anti-American tint, centered around the slogan: `` <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> decides for itself.'' `` If there are two people agreeing on Danish politics, it's <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>,'' says an election poster depicting the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> president and the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> prime minister in an embrace `` Forty-three years ago <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> again became part of the free world,'' counters a poster for the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, a member of <PERSON> Schueter </PERSON>'s four-party center-right alliance. Polls indicate that most Danes agree with the traditional anti-nuclear position. One recent survey said 82 percent of those asked favored a nuclear-free zone in <LOCATION> Scandinavia </LOCATION>, and 46 percent said they would support the idea even if it meant <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s expulsion from <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> Early polls indicate that neither the conservative-led government nor the socialist opposition may emerge as a clear winner on Tuesday, and <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> could once again be governed by an unwieldy minority coalition. Surveys trying to forecast Tuesday's outcome have been inconclusive, but several have shown modest gains for the opposition partnership of the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. In last September's election, <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON>'s coalition won 70 seats in the 179-member Folketing, and the socialist bloc took 81 seats. Each side also had two more supporters from the autonomous territories of <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Faroe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. The balance of power is held by the 11-seat <ORGANIZATION> Social-Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which usually supports the government's economic policies and the opposition's foreign and defense policies. The anti-tax <ORGANIZATION> Progress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, with 9 seats, and the far-left <ORGANIZATION> Common </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Course </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, with 4 seats, make up the balance. The shape of the next government could be determined by <PERSON> Niels </PERSON> <PERSON> Helveg </PERSON> <PERSON> Petersen </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Social-Liberal </ORGANIZATION> leader, who could even make a bid to become prime minister in the event of a deadlock between the two traditional blocs. Three other parties are contesting the election, but none is expected to pass the minimum of 2 percent of the votes cast needed to gain a seat. Polls open at 9 a.m. for the 3.9 million eligible voters. Results should be known shortly after they close at 8 p.m. <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> argues that the anti-nuclear resolution could lead to a refusal by allied ships to pull into Danish ports. `` It would be totally devastating for <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s defense,'' he told a news conference Thursday. `` We will not accept a resolution that brings our full membership of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> into doubt,'' added Foreign Minister <PERSON> Uffe </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellemann-Jensen </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader. If the resolution is allowed to stand and visiting ships are given a letter, `` the next step would be to ask for an acknowledgement of that letter, the next step would be to demand guarantees, and the next step would be the right to inspection,'' he said on Friday.
