<HEAD>With PM-Regan's Record</HEAD>
<HEAD>First Lady Kept Reagan from Taking Offensive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 First lady <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> prevented President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> from speaking out at the height of the Iran-Contra affair because her astrologer told her the time was not right to go out in public, former White House chief of staff <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> said today. `` The president was practically immobile during that period of December 1986, January and February of'87, all because the first lady was saying no, no, no he ca n't go out,'' <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> said on <ORGANIZATION> NBC-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Today'' program. `` Now she used as an excuse the fact that he had a minor operation right after the Christmas holidays. But I said, ` No, this president is going to get shot down in flames. He's not out talking to the people about Iran-Contra. He should be making his own case.' But he did n't.'' In his book, `` For the Record: From Wall Street to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>,'' which went on sale today, <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> said he believes the president's contention that he knew nothing of the Iran-Contra affair, in which proceeds from secret <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arms sales to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> were diverted to the Nicaraguan rebels, until told about it by Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> on Nov. 25, 1986 `` The president ... is a ruddy man, with bright red cheeks. He blanched when he heard <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s words. The color drained from his face, leaving his skin pasty white. ... Nobody who saw the president's reaction that afternoon could believe for a moment that he knew about the diversion of funds before <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> told him about it. He was the picture of a man to whom the inconceivable had happened,'' <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> wrote. He said that he urged the president to conteract the effects of the Iran-Contra affair by undertaking an active speaking schedule outside <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, but was balked by astrological advice to the first lady that `` harm would come to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> if he went out of the White House.'' `` By humoring her, we had given her control,'' he said of Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>, in his memoir, portrayed the president as a hesitant and unassertive chief executive controlled by a wife who relied heavily upon the predictions of an astrologer. Former press secretary <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON>, who also wrote a `` kiss and tell'' book about his years in the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, said today he was not aware of the first lady's reliance on astrology. `` I did n't see it and had no evidence of it,'' <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> said on <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>'s `` This Morning'' show. `` I've got no reason to doubt. But I never saw any crystal balls in the Cabinet Room. From time to time, strange people did come into the White House. But I did n't know that they were astrologers, if they were.'' The White House issued a brief statement about the book on Sunday that said: `` Vindictiveness and revenge are not admirable qualities, and are not worthy of comment. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>'s attempts to defame the first lady, on Mother's Day no less, are certainly in that category.'' Asked about the White House statement, <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> responded: `` They ought to know it when they see it.''
