<HEAD>Two Civilians Killed, Five Troops Injured in Golden Temple
Shootout</HEAD>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with two civilians killed,
battle continuing, PICKS UP graf 6 `The Sikh...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sikhs inside the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> opened fire today on nearby government security posts, police said, setting off a gun battle in which two civilians died and five paramilitary troops were injured. The Sikh extremists began firing automatic rifles at 1:15 p.m., and the troops returned fire with light machine guns, according to police superintendent <PERSON> Baldev </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>. The fighting continued for at least three hours. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> said it was not known if any militants where killed or injured in the exchange. The civilians killed in the crossfire outside the Golden Temple complex were identified by police as <PERSON> Venod </PERSON> <PERSON> Kumar </PERSON>, 30, a Hindu who worked with the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Dilip </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaur </PERSON>, an 80-year-old Sikh. Among the injured was the deputy inspector general of the paramilitary <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> S.S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Virk </PERSON>. He was out of danger after surgery for a bullet wound on his chin, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Virk </PERSON> and other senior paramilitary officers had gone to government security posts on rooftops near the shrine to look at a bunker Sikh militants were building at the western end of the Golden Temple complex. Police said the militants opened fire from at least 16 sites in the temple complex, mainly with Chinese-made AK-47 automatic rifles. The troops returned fire with light machine guns, according to <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>. Shops and businesses in bazaars around the Golden Temple closed their shutters, and an indefinite curfew was imposed on the old, walled, central part of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> to keep civilians indoors. More than 1,000 police and paramilitary troops were rushed to the temple to seal exits and prevent people from entering. Sikh extremists have been waging a guerrilla campaign since 1982 for more political autonomy or an independent homeland for Sikhs in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. The Golden Temple is <LOCATION> Sikhism </LOCATION>'s holiest shrine. In June 1984, the Indian army stormed the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> to drive out militants, and more than 1,200 people were killed. Later that year, Prime Minister <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> was assassinated by two Sikh bodguards in revenge for the raid, setting off anti-Sikh rioting in which 2,000 people died. The gun battle today was the worst in a series that began shortly after <PERSON> Jasbir </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> <PERSON> Rode </PERSON> was restored as the temple's chief priest in early March. Rode had been in custody under the government's anti-terrorism rules, but was freed in an effort by Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> to placate the extremists and lure them into negotiations. Since Rode's return, there have been persistent reports that the militants have been building bunkers and firing ports in the temple complex. The militants fired on police outside the temple last week when security forces tried to arrest a Sikh militant as he was heading for the shrine. The militant escaped and fled into the temple, but he was believed wounded. Sikhs, whose religion was founded about 500 years ago as an alternative to <LOCATION> Hinduism </LOCATION> and Islam, claim they are discriminated against by <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s majority Hindus. Sikhs make up less than 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million population but are a majority in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. Meanwhile, five more people were reported killed by <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> extremists in overnight attacks in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> reported. The slayings followed an attack by the radicals in neighboring <LOCATION> Haryana </LOCATION> on Saturday in which 13 Hindus were killed during a wedding party. The latest killings raised to about 940 the number of deaths blamed on the Sikh separatists this year. The rate of killings is more than twice that of 1987, when 1,000 people were killed by Sikh extremists. Most victims have been Hindus or moderate Sikhs in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>.
