<TEXT>
 After getting a replacement for a juror described as `` incoherent,'' the jury returned to court today for a sixth day of deliberations on whether <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> should die for his part in the six 1973 slayings of the <PERSON> Alday </PERSON> family. Superior Court Judge <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> on Sunday morning excused a juror and replaced her with one of three remaining alternates. At 3:30 p.m., he sent the jurors back to their hotel with instructions to return today. The jury met briefly with <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> this morning before resuming its talks. Defense attorney <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> West </PERSON> moved again Sunday for <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> to declare the jury deadlocked. That would bring <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> an automatic life sentence. <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> was one of three men originally convicted and sentenced to die for the 1973 slayings of six members of the <PERSON> Ned </PERSON> <PERSON> Alday </PERSON> family in <LOCATION> Seminole </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. The verdicts were thrown out in 1985 by a federal appeals court which cited pretrial publicity. The juror who was excused did not accompany the other jurors to the DeKalb County Courthouse Sunday morning. She arrived separately and then testified before <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>. Much of her testimony was inaudible. Several times, she said, `` They put a bug in my ear. Remember <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Alday </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Alday </PERSON> was raped and killed in a field near the mobile home where her husband, <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Alday </PERSON>, and four other Alday men were killed on May 14, 1973. A deputy assigned to watch the sequestered jurors testified the juror `` was mumbling nonsense. She was not coherent. She is not physically or mentally capable to continue.'' The deputy said the woman could be made