he rhinoceros appeared. `` We did not hear the sounds of any animal on that morning,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. `` But all of sudden, I saw a rhino rushing towards -LRB- me -RRB- ... charging from a distance of about 15 feet. `` I turned around and started to run. But I realized that I could not escape, so I used my hands ... pushing to keep the animal away. `` It gored my chest,'' he said. `` The animal hit me about 12 times. Sometimes I was able to roll. I did -LRB- this so -RRB- ... the animal would miss me.'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> received four major wounds to his head, chest, leg and buttocks. His wife said the main danger of such an attack comes from the animal's razor-sharp lower teeth, not from its huge horn. `` He was extremely brave,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Hemanta </PERSON> <PERSON> Mishra </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> King </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mahendra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nature </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Katmandu </LOCATION>. `` He handled it very coolly.'' <PERSON> Mishra </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> -LRB- </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minn. </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- Pioneer Press Dispatch by telephone that the rhinoceros had charged <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>'s son. There was no time to get the boy out of the way, so the father charged the rhino to draw it away from his son, <PERSON> Mishra </PERSON> told the newspaper. Others put the boy into a tree, then threw stones and sticks at the rhinoceros to drive it off, <PERSON> Mishra </PERSON> was quoted as saying. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> was in the park conducting a small-mammal survey sponsored by his university, the <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> and the nature trust, <PERSON> Mishra </PERSON> said. The animal that attacked <PERSON> 