<HEAD>Military Fugitive Returned To Argentina For Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cashiered army Gen. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s most-wanted military fugitive, was extradited from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> today to face trial for the murders of suspected leftists in the 1970s. The extradition was ordered April 27 in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Jensen </PERSON>, who ruled <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> could be tried in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> on charges of 39 murders allegedly committed by troops under his command. If convicted, the maximum sentence is life in prison. The 64-year-old former general fled <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> in 1984 and was arrested by federal marshals in <LOCATION> Foster </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> suburb, where he has been living under an assumed name. Federal Police Chief <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Pirker </PERSON> confirmed that <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> arrived at Ezeira International Airport at 9:05 a.m. aboard an <ORGANIZATION> Aerolinas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Argentinas </ORGANIZATION> flight from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Pirker </PERSON> said <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> was accompanied by five guards, but he refused to provide further details. The handcuffed prisoner was escorted off the plane by federal police officers, witnesses said, was put aboard an armored vehicle and taken to federal police headquarters in downtown <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> was stripped of his military rank in April 1984 after he was declared `` in rebellion'' when he failed to appear before a military tribunal for questioning in connection with the abduction, torture and murder of suspected leftists. At least 9,000 Argentines disappeared in a so-called `` dirty war'' waged against leftists by the military regime that seized power in 1976 after ousting former President <PERSON> Isabel </PERSON> <PERSON> Peron </PERSON>. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s trial was personally ordered by President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> shortly after he took office in December 1983, ending nearly eight years of rightist military rule. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> was commander of the Buenos Aires-based 1st <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> from 1976 to 1978, when he was promoted to head of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Staff </ORGANIZATION>. He retired in 1981 and was named president of the state oil monopoly <ORGANIZATION> Yacimientos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroliferos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fiscales </ORGANIZATION>, a post he held until 1982. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> sought <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s extradition on 43 separate charges of murder. He also has been accused of 635 cases of human rights abuse as well as misappropriation of more than $ 2 million while he headed the state oil monopoly. In approving <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s extradition, <PERSON> Jensen </PERSON> ruled he could be tried on 39 murder murders, as well as an additional charge of forging a passport renewal. But the judge rejected the four other murder charges after ruling that identification of the victims was inadequate. He also ordered the dismissal of 23 kidnapping charges, saying the 5-year legal deadline for filing the charges expired in 1984. Under the extradition law, <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> can be tried only on charges for which extradition is approved.
