<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 A swarm of tornadoes and powerful storms struck the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> with high winds and hail, killing a construction worker, damaging roofs, knocking down power lines and leaving thousands blacked out today. More than 80 tornadoes or tornado-like storms touched down Sunday _ 32 in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, 25 in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and 22 in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and one each in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, and at least 160 reports of thunderstorms with wind gusts over 50 mph, some with baseball-sized hail, the weather service said. One man, a 39-year-old construction worker, was killed Sunday night when a house he was building collapsed on him in high winds in Crown Point, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, about 15 miles south of <PERSON> Gary </PERSON>, officials said today. Sunday marked the region's second day of violent weather. In rural <LOCATION> Gretna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, a 29-year-old woman and her 2-year-old daughter died after a tornado struck their mobile home Saturday night. Storm damage reports covered eastern <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, northeast <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, from <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> through southern <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and western <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>. In eastern <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, more than 5,000 <ORGANIZATION> Iowa-Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> customers were without power for several hours Sunday, and several thousand <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> And </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Light </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> customers were blacked out in the <LOCATION> Des </LOCAT