<HEAD>The Down-to-Earth Side of the Space Agency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANGLEY RESEARCH CENTER, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two years ago, in his State of the Union message, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> launched a venture to take aviation into the 21st century. `` We are going forward with research on a new Orient Express that could, by the end of the next decade, take off from <LOCATION> Dulles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> -LRB- outside <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> -RRB-, accelerate up to 25 times the speed of sound, attaining low Earth orbit or flying to <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> within two hours,'' he said. Research on an aerospace plane already had been going on for years in the part of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> that gets little public attention _ <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s first A, for aeronautics, sometimes also known as the little A. `` We are called the space agency by many, probably including yourself,'' <PERSON> Jeremiah </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Creedon </PERSON>, the director for flight systems at the <ORGANIZATION> Langley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, told a visitor. `` Many of us here think the -LRB- aeronautics -RRB- A is a large one.'' Together with other <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> research centers _ Ames and <PERSON> Dryden </PERSON> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> _ <LOCATION> Langley </LOCATION>'s business is to develop technology and to pass it on, without cost, to aircraft companies. Few planes fly today without engines, designs, materials and structures conceived at <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>. No single company alone could afford the agency's $ 2 billion investment in wind tunnels. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s rosy prediction followed years of research by <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> engineers before they decided that the aerospace plane, dubbed the X-30, was even possible. In the summer of 1990, engineers will decide whether to actually build the X-30. If the answer is yes, it could begin flight tests that would finish when the 21st century is ushered in. It will be the largest experimental aircraft project ever undertaken by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, costing $ 3.3 billion. The idea of the X-30 is to develop technologies that will be useful for planes at a slower speed _ such as 3 -LCB- times the speed of sound, or Mach 3.5. The military, and perhaps package delivery firms such as <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parcel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, are the only ones that have use for a plane flying 25 times the speed of sound. `` There is tremendous potential for all kinds of vehicles operating at high Mach numbers,'' said <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Dwoyer </PERSON>, manager of hypersonic technology at <LOCATION> Langley </LOCATION>. `` The national aerospace program is aimed at an experimental aircraft to demonstrate technologies for this family of hypersonic aircraft.'' Although the big airplane manufacturers have little interest in building a Mach 25 plane, they do want a craft capable of flying between <ORGANIZATION> Mach </ORGANIZATION> 2 and <ORGANIZATION> Mach </ORGANIZATION> 3.5, for the years 2000 to 2010. At Mach 2.7, a trip from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> would take just under four hours. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> did research in the 1960s on a supersonic transport, the SST, but dropped the program in 1970 because of costs and environmental concerns. `` The nation essentially allowed its entire research and technology base in hypersonics to disappear,'' said <PERSON> Dwoyer </PERSON>. `` We are bringing tunnels on line that have n't operated in almost 20 years with instrumentation systems that are 20 years-plus old.'' Meanwhile, the British and French produced the Concorde, capable of twice the speed of sound. The Concorde was designed with 1960s technology and can barely carry enough fuel to make it from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> across the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>. The business of the future is with the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rim </LOCATION> _ <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> _ where a fast, 6,000-mile airplane is needed. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, director of aeronautics at <LOCATION> Langley </LOCATION>, sees a real need for a long-range SST. The airlines that serve that market are pushing hard, he said. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> are trying to determine how many Mach 3.5 planes might be needed by the year 2000. `` It looks like it's on the order of 300 to 400 airplanes for the world market,'' said <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> _ holding out the prospect of a world market for an American plane that would help untilt the trade balance. But the British, the French, the Soviets and the Japanese also have ambitious aeronautics programs. Despite such competition, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> treats its aeronautics limb as a poor relative. Out of a $ 9 billion <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> budget, aeronautics R & amp; D this year gets only $ 430 million; $ 53 million of that is earmarked for the aerospace plane. The money issue is a sensitive one at <LOCATION> Langley </LOCATION>. `` I think we are grossly underfunded,'' said <PERSON> Dwoyer </PERSON>. `` On a $ 400-million-a-year program, we can not maintain our capability.'' Until 1970, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> jet transport industry had 90 percent of the long-range market. Now that's down to 70 percent. `` For 70 years you could go to any airport in the world and look out on the ramp and you see ` Made in the <LOCATION> U.S.A. </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said. Now the European-built <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION>, a superb plane, can be seen at most airports, too.
