<FIRST>r w AM-PollutionOptimism     05-09 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pollution Optimism,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Rules on Gasoline Evaporation May Help Clean Up Hidden Air
Polluter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cities may have been made significantly smoggier than previously predicted by an unrecognized form of auto pollution _ a source that planned new regulations should clear up, according to several analysts. The newly recognized source is evaporation of gasoline from fuel systems while cars are running. The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> has been assuming these `` running losses'' could be neglected in assessing the formation of ozone, the major component of smog, from volatile compounds like gasoline. New findings suggest the amount of gasoline that evaporates from a car's fuel system when the vehicle is being used on a hot day may be five times to 25 times greater than the amount of unburned gasoline that is permitted to escape in exhaust: 2 grams to 10 grams per mile in `` running losses'' compared with 0.41 grams out the tailpipe. Ten grams of gasoline is about half a liquid ounce. `` If all these things fall into place, it's logical to expect this is a big source and another explanation that could be offered as to why attainment -LRB- of the air quality standards -RRB- has been so hard,'' said <PERSON> Tad </PERSON> <PERSON> Wysor </PERSON>, an engineer in <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s Emissions Control Technology Division in <LOCATION> Ann </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aror </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION> `` Official predictions have been under-predicting'' future improvement, said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Austin </PERSON>, a partner in <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, air pollution consultants. All cars must pass tests for gasoline emissions while parked. Newly proposed EPA regulations are designed to reduce this stationary evaporation, along with vapors lost during refueling. They will require refiners to cut summertime gasoline volatility _ its tendency to evaporate _ by 22 percent from the current, often exceeded, voluntary standard. They also will require the existing auto vapor recovery system to be enlarged to capture refueling vapors. Ozone worsens breathing problems. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> last week released the names of 68 urban and rural areas where air did not meet the federal ozone standard in 1987, up from the 62 on the previous year's list. Though <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said a warm summer in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> in 1987 helped push up ozone violations, environmental groups immediately claimed that the data showed that the smog problem was getting worse. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has known for years that today's gasoline volatility _ 11.5 pounds of vapor pressure is the summer standard in much of the country _ will cause cars to flunk its stationary emissions test badly. The fuel used in that test must be 9.0 pounds, the pressure the agency wants to make the mandatory maximum. Nine pounds was typical of gasoline in 1975 when test specifications were drawn up. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON>, director of automotive emissions control for <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s environmental activities staff, said <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> has found that emissions on one part of the stationary test are 16 times greater with 11.5 pound fuel than with 9.0 pound fuel. <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> outlined one explanation for the unexpectedly high running losses at a briefing on vapor recovery systems sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> last week: the near-abandonment of carburetors for fuel injectors by engine manufacturers. Fuel injection systems continuously recycle uninjected fuel back to the tank. Accordig to <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON>, the returning fuel picks up heat in the engine compartment, making fuel in the tank run 20 degrees warmer than the outside air. This heat raises the pressure of the higher-volatility fuel. That appears to overwhelm the existing charcoal cannister in the vapor recovery system, leaving the vapor nowhere to go but to the atmosphere. <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> said he believed the running loss problem was mostly a warm-climate phenomenon affecting `` probably less than 1 percent of miles traveled'' nationwide. But <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>, a consultant often used by environmental groups, said, `` One percent sounds like a low number to me.'' `` The ozone problem is a warm-weather problem. ... We have a lot of places in this country with plenty of hot days in the summertime,'' <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
