<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Danish election campaign drew to a close Monday in a race that could decide the strength of <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s commitment to the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> alliance. Conservative Prime Minister <PERSON> Poul </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON>, in a final appeal before Tuesday's vote, said he sought a mandate to restore <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s credibility in the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> called the election after he failed to block a move in parliament last month to toughen <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s anti-nuclear stance. The move was sponsored by the opposition Social Democrats. If implemented, the resolution would require <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> to notify each visiting warship of <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s peacetime ban on nuclear weapons in its territory. The resolution was seen as a challenge to <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s policy of keeping a nuclear option. Under that policy, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and British ships refuse to say whether they are armed with nuclear weapons. <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON>, who has led minority governments for six years, called the snap election on the issue just eight months after the last vote. It was <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s 19th election since War War II _ a <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> record _ and the first time since then that <LOCATION> Danes </LOCATION> were asked to vote mainly on a foreign policy issue. Twelve parties are contesting the election, three more than are currently represented in the 179-member Folketing, or parliament. <PERSON> Schueter </PERSON>'s four-party alliance of center-right parties controls 70 seats. <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> said in an interview published Monday that the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION>' motion had undermined <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s credibility with its Western allies. `` This is a referendum about <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>,'' he told the conservative newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Berlingske </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tidende </ORGANIZATION>. He also said he expected a long period of post-election haggling to form a workable coalition, and that he hoped for a broad alliance that would command a majority in parliament. He did not rule out a partnership with the Social Democrats, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s largest party. `` There is an undeniable need for a group of parties to thoroughly discuss the major political problems,'' he said. `` I would go so far as to say that it is not advisable to appoint a prime minister or a government if there is the least doubt that a new majority is behind them,'' <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> said. Pre-election polls indicated another election stand-off is likely between the two major blocs, with the Social-Liberals again holding the balance. The party, with 11 seats, supports the government on domestic policy and the opposition on foreign issues. As many as half a million voters, nearly one in eight, will decide at the last minute how they will vote, said <PERSON> Ole </PERSON> <PERSON> Borre </PERSON>, political science professor at <ORGANIZATION> Aarhus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` Many have n't decided who they will vote for, or whether they will vote at all,'' he told <PERSON> Berlingske </PERSON> <PERSON> Tidende </PERSON>. Turnout last September was 86 percent, about average in <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, where 3.9 million citizens are registered to vote. Polls show the far-right <ORGANIZATION> Progress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, campaigning on a platform of deep tax cuts and limiting immigration, is the only party likely to advance strongly. In the latest poll published Sunday, the <ORGANIZATION> Progress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> took eight percent, compared with the 4.8 percent it won in the previous election. Social Democratic leader <PERSON> Svend </PERSON> <PERSON> Auken </PERSON> has denied that his party is anti-NATO, and has accused <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> of exaggerating the meaning of the resolution. <PERSON> Auken </PERSON>, 44, facing the electorate for the first time as party leader, is taking over from former Prime Minister <PERSON> Anker </PERSON> <PERSON> Joergensen </PERSON>, who resigned after the last round of balloting. The Social Democrats campaigned under the slogan `` <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> decides for itself.'' Posters depicting President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> embracing Prime Minister <PERSON> Magaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> implied that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> wanted to dictate <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s nuclear policies. The Social Democrats, who dominated Danish politics for 40 years until they relinquished power in 1982, led <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> into <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> as a founding member in 1949. The party drifted toward a hardline anti-nuclear stance shortly after it became the opposition and sponsored a motion to stop <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s payments toward the stationing of cruise missiles in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.
