> while they attempted to make further revisions. The House last week passed a technical corrections resolution that also would drop restrictions on export of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> oil. That measure simply would authorize an official known as the enrolling clerk to dot the i's and cross the t's in the bill _ and erase the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> provisions. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said he hoped to bring up the resolution in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> as soon as possible, but would need the unanimous consent of senators to do so. He said he would discuss that with Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan. It was expected the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> would take up the resolution this week. Major provisions of the trade bill would streamline procedures for use of import restrictions to aid <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry and to retaliate against international trade violations. Scores of other provisions range from billions of dollars in agricultural subsidies to repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil companies.
