<DATELINE>RIVERSIDE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An error by an air traffic controller may have contributed to the 1987 jet crash that killed actor <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, the Riverside Press-Enterprise reported. A controller warning, which incorrectly gave the location of <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gorgonio </LOCATION>, may have caused <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> to turn too sharply and lose control of his F-4C Phantom jet, said veteran <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> test pilot <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> LeVier </PERSON>. <PERSON> LeVier </PERSON> made his conclusions after reviewing an analysis by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, according to reports obtained by the newspaper through the Freedom of Information Act. <PERSON> LeVier </PERSON>'s conclusions were published Sunday. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, a captain in the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and son of entertainer <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, and his weapons officer, Capt. <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortiz </PERSON>, 39, died March 21, 1987, when the jet traveling at 600 mph crashed into a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> canyon. The accident report draws no conclusions about what happened during the last seconds of <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>'s flight. <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> pilots and air traffic controllers declined to comment on what might have caused the crash which killed <PERSON> Ortiz </PERSON> and the 35-year-old <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>. But <PERSON> LeVier </PERSON> said it is clear <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> made too sharp a left turn, probably in a moment of panic as he feared hitting the mountain ahead. If you turn the F-4 too quickly, the nose will pull the airplane up, disrupting the plane's aerodynamics, said <PERSON> LeVier </PERSON>, who has tested 70 aircraft during his 46-year career. `` The airplane simply becomes uncontrollable. The ... thing goes ape,'' <PERSON> LeVier </PERSON> said. According to the accident analysis, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> was at 11,500 feet, flying in clouds and had not heard two previous instructions to turn left. His plane was far off its route and heading toward the peak. The controller reportedly told the pilot he was three miles south of a 13,000-foot peak. But the analysis said the peak is 11,502 feet, not 13,000 feet, and <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>'s aircraft was 8 -LCB- miles from the summit, not three miles. Air Guard Maj. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Mensik </PERSON>, spokesman for the Guard in <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, said the controller's erroneous communication with <PERSON> Martin-Ortiz </PERSON> was a contributing factor to the crash. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials at <ORGANIZATION> Ontario </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION> said the controller who handled the <ORGANIZATION> Martin-Ortiz </ORGANIZATION> flight committed no error. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>, the controller's supervisor, said there were many factors, including the work-load and weather, that might cause the controller to miscalculate the distance of the fighter from the mountain. He said his office has not read the latest accident investigation report. A spokesman for the pilot's family called <PERSON> LeVier </PERSON>'s analysis an assumption. <PERSON> Mort </PERSON> <PERSON> Viner </PERSON> said he had heard other equally plausible causes for the crash.
