<HEAD>Comptroller's Report Shows Deficiencies in Readiness for War</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Israeli army does not have enough shells for its tanks and artillery, which could affect its readiness for war, the government comptroller's office declared in a report issued Monday. It also said the military does not keep close enough track of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid. `` Ammunition stockpiles are a central part of army preparedness for war,'' the report said. `` The findings of our survey show significant malfunctions which must be rectified as soon as possible.'' Comptroller <PERSON> Yaacov </PERSON> <PERSON> Maltz </PERSON> presented the 983-page report at a news conference. About one-fifth of it was devoted to the military. It said management problems have eroded the profitability of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s large weapons industry, and investigators could not determine exactly what use was made of $ 1.8 billion in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid in 1986 because it was lumped with other foreign-currency expenditures. <PERSON> Maltz </PERSON>'s report did not suggest the money was misspent but said records of how it was used were inadequate. `` Some of the budget in foreign currency is allocated along with <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> assistance funds, without any differentiation to monitor what is being purchased with what money,'' it said. The comptroller said the investigations, conducted last year, found shortages of essential weapons. He blamed them on cuts in the defense budget, red tape and a need to divert funds to other projects he did not name. His report said surveys found inadequate supplies of 105mm tank shells, 155mm and 175mm artillery shells and mortars. In keeping with army regulations, no figures were given. <PERSON> Maltz </PERSON> said a more detailed report was delivered to the military. <PERSON> Eitan </PERSON> <PERSON> Haber </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said the army is prohibited by law from responding publicly to such reports. Other parts of the <PERSON> Maltz </PERSON> document said training courses for soldiers were inadequate and lists of ammunition storage depots were outdated, raising questions about public safety. It cited shortages of emergency medical supplies, food, water and shelters in northern settlements bordering <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. A section on the weapons industry criticized one of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s leading arms developers, <ORGANIZATION> Rafael </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armament </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, for losing money in major arms deals Most losses are covered by the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. It mentioned a $ 35 million deal by <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> in which the military was expected to absorb a $ 3.3 million loss. Instead, projected losses had reached $ 11.7 million and could total nearly $ 15 million, according to the report. Because of censorship regulations it gave no further details of the 1966 contract, but said `` the economic viability of the project was not adequately checked.'' Elsewhere in his report, <PERSON> Maltz </PERSON> was critical of the public health system, which has been disrupted by strikes and other job actions by doctors, nurses and maintenance staff. The report said more than 30,000 Israelis had to wait up to three years for operations as a result.
