<HEAD>West German Cadet Ship Visits Haifa, First By Military Unit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAIFA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A West German cadet ship sailed into this <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> port Monday in the first visit by a German military unit to the Jewish state. The West German ambassador cited the port call as an example of solid bilateral relations. Some Israelis, however, said they felt uneasy at the sight of German military men strolling through <LOCATION> Haifa </LOCATION>'s streets. `` They are young people and I have nothing against them,'' said <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON> <PERSON> Biermann </PERSON>, 54, a bank clerk who lived through World War II as a boy in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>. `` But when I see a German uniform, I still feel a stab in my heart,'' he added as seven cadets wearing traditional white-and-blue sailor suits passed him on <LOCATION> Haifa </LOCATION>'s bustling main street. The three-mast sailing ship <PERSON> Gorch </PERSON> <PERSON> Fock </PERSON> is in <LOCATION> Haifa </LOCATION> for a five-day stay that will include a soccer match between German and <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> cadets, visits to <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> families and a trip to the Holocaust memorial Yad Vashem in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>. The port call in <LOCATION> Haifa </LOCATION> is part of an 11-month sail around the world for the Gorch Forck before it returns to its homeport, <LOCATION> Kiel </LOCATION>, in June. Stops have included <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oman </LOCATION> on the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. West German Ambassador <PERSON> Wilhelm </PERSON> <PERSON> Haas </PERSON> described the relationship between the defense establishments of <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> as good, and said `` the visit of the ship fits very well into this picture.'' <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is selling ammunition, aircraft and remote-control vehi