<HEAD>Weekend Blaze Keeps Phones Silent; Major Airports Affected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A weekend fire at an <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> switching station kept telephones idle for 35,000 customers in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s western suburbs Monday and caused delays at major airports No remedies were expected until at least midweek, <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> officials said. Crews at the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s control center in <LOCATION> Aurora </LOCATION> were using a backup phone system, but the lack of full service meant controllers had to stagger the arrival of flights by 20 miles. `` Major trouble, major,'' said <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mort </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelstein </PERSON>. Fire departments from 15 communities battled the fire at the <LOCATION> Hinsdale </LOCATION> station, west of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, for three hours before it was brought under control Sunday evening. The facility houses computerized switching equipment that serves customers by connecting their local calls directly to the number dialed and routing long-distance calls. Customers in the suburbs of <LOCATION> Hinsdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Willowbrook </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Clarendon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> and parts of <LOCATION> Darien </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Burr </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION> and unincorporated <ORGANIZATION> Oak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brook </ORGANIZATION> lost all service, said <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Littel </PERSON>. Some pockets farther south had limited phone service because some of their calls go through the <LOCATION> Hinsdale </LOCATION> station, Ms. <PERSON> Littel </PERSON> said. She said phones were dead for 35,000 customers, but the number of consumers with only partial interruption was unknown. The cause of the fire was unknown. At <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Edelstein </PERSON> said 55 to 60 incoming flights were allowed per hour, down from the normal level of 75. The <LOCATION> Aurora </LOCATION> air traffic control center also handles traffic for <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s Midway Airport. O'Hare's biggest tenant, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, had delays of at least 30 minutes, spokesman <PERSON> Matt </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonring </PERSON> said.
