<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> said today serious differences have developed between the <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> over on-site verification provisions of the medium-range missile treaty and urged the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> not to open debate on the pact until they are resolved. `` There are serious problems and until they are resolved I think it would be very difficult to proceed with a full-fledged debate in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>,'' said Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Maine </LOCATION>. `` My feeling is that until these disputes are resolved we should not proceed,'' <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said. Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Boren </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., the chairman of the intelligence panel, agreed `` There are serious ambiguities that remain. There simply has not been a meeting of the minds on verification problems. There are a number of things that have to be resolved,'' he said. Soviet officials have been quoted in recent weeks as backing away from certain on-site inspection procedures spelled out by the treaty. <PERSON> Boren </PERSON> told reporters: `` This is no way to begin a relationship under a treaty as important as this if these deliberate ambiguities remain.'' If they are not resolved quickly, `` I would be very reluctant to proceed,'' <PERSON> Boren </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said that administration officials have said they are encouraged by the nature of recent contacts with Soviet officials on the dispute over the treaty. But <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said he is `` less optimistic'' that differences can be resolved quickly. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> debate on ratification of the treaty had been tenatively been set to begin Wednesday. But <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> said Monday that he will not permit the debate to begin as long as serious problems remain. The Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty requires the elimination of all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet missiles with a range of between 300 and 3,400 miles worldwide.
