<HEAD>Report Says Agency Not Buying Equipment Wisely</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Congressional investigators have determined that the <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is wasting millions of tax dollars on unneeded equipment it can not use, a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee chairman said Monday. Rep. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> English, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., said a one-year review by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> found the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> apparently `` has no consistent method of deciding what it needs or how to purchase equpment that would fill those needs The result is that at best we're getting equipment that does n't really do the job.'' The <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> responded Monday to concerns raised in the report with plans to establish a research and development steering committee that will develop procurement procedures based on some <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> recommendations, said spokesman <PERSON> Verne </PERSON> <PERSON> Jervis </PERSON>. The INS planning office, which includes research and development, will also be moved so that it reports directly to the INS commissioner's office, where it will receive `` enhanced visibility and increased access to top management,'' <PERSON> Jervis </PERSON> said. English said he was concerned efforts in the war on drugs were being hurt by the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION>' apparent waste of `` millions of dollars on equipment the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> ca n't really use.'' `` There's no question that <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> and particularly the <ORGANIZATION> Border </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION> are underfunded when it comes to the war on drugs. Therefore, money wasted on unwise purchases is money that can not be used to halt the flow of drugs across our borders,'' he said in a statement. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report, to be released Thursday at a hearing by English's government information, justice and agriculture subcommittee, found that `` the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> had no defined, formal method of technology selection.'' In one instance, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> found the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> had ordered the purchase of 11 undercover vans outfitted with an extendable infrared scope for monitoring the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> borders, at a cost of more than $ 130,000 for each vehicle, even though operational tests were incomplete. And the report said the infrared scopes, which could have been used to support linewatch operations in various Border Patrol sectors, sat unused for at least 7 -LCB- months at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huachuca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION> `` Had those scopes been available for use in detection in various sectors, some <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> agents could have been deployed for other activities. The value of the agents' work that was foregone by the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> as a result is estimated to be in the range of $ 1.4 million to $ 3.4 million,'' the report said.
