accounts of police breaking down cottage doors, arresting people.
No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police broke down the doors of a country cottage where a dissident group planned to meet and arrested five people Monday. Sources said 70 other activists met nearby and founded an alternative party to the Communist Party. The new group calls itself the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. It seeks a multiparty parliamentary democracy in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, independent trade unions, a new constitution and withdrawal of Soviet troops from Eastern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and areas of the present <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> seized in World War II. Over the weekend, 60 of its supporters were reported arrested in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and one of the group's founders, <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Mityunov </PERSON>, said Monday that 14 remained in jail after being arrested Sunday night. Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has called for more democratic election procedures, including multiple-candidate elections. But the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> he heads has given no sign that it will accept any organized opposition to its monopoly on political power, which is enshrined in the Soviet constitution. <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Babitsky </PERSON>, an editor of the dissident journal Glasnost, said uniformed and plainclothes police encircled a cottage in the woods near the village of <LOCATION> Kratovo </LOCATION>, 25 miles southeast of the capital, where the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> planned to meet Monday afternoon. The two-floor wooden cottage has been used for meetings of the staff of Glasnost, an unofficial publication that takes its title from the Russian word for openness. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has used glasnost to describe some of his reforms. `` A militia officer asked to see our identification documents, but we refused, saying there was no grounds,'' <PERSON> Babitsky </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. `` He then went for reinforcements, and about 50 uniformed militia, plainclothesmen and <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> officers suddenly appeared. They had obviously been waiting nearby.'' <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON>, a former political prisoner who is the founding editor of Glasnost, was arrested on the lawn outside, <PERSON> Babitsky </PERSON> said. `` We closed all five doors to the dacha, but police broke them in,'' he added. <PERSON> Babitsky </PERSON> said he was arrested along with <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Petrovsky </PERSON>, who also works with Glasnost; <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuzin </PERSON>, a founder of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, and a man known only as <PERSON> Volodya </PERSON> who <PERSON> Babitsky </PERSON> said was in the vicinity of the cottage by chance. <PERSON> Babitsky </PERSON> said he was held for almost nine hours without being charged, then released by police shortly before 9 p.m. with no explanation. Another dissident was in the country house, but fled before he could be detained, another Glasnost editor, <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Krivov </PERSON>, said in a telephone interview Monday night. <PERSON> Krivov </PERSON> said people who talked to <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON> at the police station in <LOCATION> Ilinskoye </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Kratovo </LOCATION>, reported that <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON> `` was frisked, his clothes were ripped, and a large sum of money he was carrying was taken.'' Mityunov reported by telephone that about 70 members of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, kept from meeting at the cottage, gathered at a nearby rural club. `` In a half-hour, they adopted the basic program for the party, a declaration and a charter,'' he said. `` I think the formation of the party is a big event in the unification of forces to fight against the bureaucratic totalitarian regime,'' said <PERSON> Mityunov </PERSON>, a former member of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> who was fired from his editorial job on state-run Radio <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in 1986. <PERSON> Babitsky </PERSON> said he learned from <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON>' wife <PERSON> Tamara </PERSON> that the Glasnost editor-in-chief was sentenced to seven days in jail for resisting authorities. `` I saw him arrested, and he did not such thing,'' <PERSON> Babitsky </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Petrovsky </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kuzin </PERSON> and the man known as <PERSON> Volodya </PERSON> received five-day jail terms, but the dissidents group did not know on what charges, <PERSON> Babitsky </PERSON> said. The Kratovo cottage was sealed by police and newspapers and books inside may have been taken away by investigators, <PERSON> Babitsky </PERSON> said. ` I fear this action may be the defeat of ` Glasnost,''' he added. The typewritten journal began appearing last year. Kratovo is located in a region foreigners are barred by law from visiting. The Soviet constitution calls the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> the `` leading and guiding force of Soviet society and the nucleus of its political system.'' Although new dissident groups and independent publications have sprung up up throughout the country since hundreds of political prisoners were freed in early 1987, authorities have crushed efforts to form an opposition to the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>.
