<HEAD>Nearly 60 Million Acres Idled Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farmers idled about 59.9 million acres of cropland under 1987 acreage reduction programs, an area larger than all of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> combined, <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> figures showed Monday. The preliminary report for compliance in the 1987 programs said the acreage represented about 87 percent of the base acreage for wheat, feed grains, cotton and rice. In 1986, by comparison, farmers idled 44.6 million acres, or 82 percent of their total base for those crops. Wheat farmers idled 23.8 million acres last year, followed by corn, 23 million acres; sorghum, 4 million; barley, 2.9 million; oats, 800,000; cotton, 3.8 million; and rice, 1.6 million.
