<HEAD>Pentagon Says US Can't Afford to Fall Further Behind in Star Wars
Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can not afford from a military perspective to fall further behind in its `` Star Wars'' research, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, in a required annual report on the Strategic Defense Initiative, or Star Wars program, said even 3 percent annual increases in funding for the research would not be enough to `` keep pace'' with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The Russians continue to modernize their offensive as well as defensive weaponry, gradually improving their ability to destroy <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces with a surprise attack, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> report said. `` The resulting asymmetry between <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces has led to a destabilizing situation, one that must be redressed,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said. A Star Wars defense system that could shoot down Soviet missiles offers the promise of a more stable peace, the Pentagon insisted. The mere process of attempting to develop such a system complicates Soviet military planning and strains the Russian economy. If, on the other hand, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> continues to cut deeply into Star Wars funding, `` the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will not only waste its greatest leverage _ the innovation possible in a free society _ but it can not expect to do more than react to Soviet initiatives in strategic defense,'' the Pentagon said. `` We are faced with either delaying the time when a decision on whether to deploy defenses could be made, or eliminating some technology efforts, thereby reducing the number of defense options that can support a decision.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> included the new plea for funding in a report that runs to several hundred pages, reviewing the work done over the past year in various technological fields. Release of the report comes just a week after <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> warned he would recommend that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> veto the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s fiscal 1989 budget bill if cuts are made to the $ 4.5 billion requested for Star Wars. While the administration has been forced to abandon its goal of increasing overall defense spending by 3 percent a year, it continues to request steep hikes for Star Wars. Since 1983, however, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has cut almost $ 5 billion from the roughly $ 18 billion requested for <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wars </ORGANIZATION>. `` While the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has increased -LRB- Star Wars -RRB- funding every year, the difference between what the administration has requested and what the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has appropriated is so large that it has had a substantial and increasingly detrimental impact on the program,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> asserted.
