<HEAD>Acclaimed Science Fiction Author Dies At 80</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY33</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARMEL, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinlein </PERSON>, whose science fiction explored the future while questioning the morals and beliefs of the present, has died at the age of 80, it was announced Monday. <PERSON> Heinlein </PERSON>, who added the word `` grok'' to the language and dreamed up the water bed, was ranked with <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON> <PERSON> Asimov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON> among the greatest practitioners of science fiction. His fiction explored the seeming contraditions of his own philosophy, which embraced libertarianism and a passionate faith in the military. He died of heart failure Sunday at his home in this small tourist community about 130 miles south of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Monterey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Coroner's office. <PERSON> Heinlein </PERSON> had suffered for many years from emphysema and had undergone numerous operations, including one to relieve restricted blood flow to his brain. `` <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinlein </PERSON> has been writing science fiction now for 48 years and from the very start he was recognized as a grand master,'' <PERSON> Asimov </PERSON> said Monday. `` In 1975 the <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fiction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> set up just such an award, and he was the first to get it. There was no argument, much like <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> becoming the first president.'' <PERSON> Asimov </PERSON> said he and <PERSON> Heinlein </PERSON> had served together in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> during World War II, during <PERSON> Heinlein </PERSON>'s second <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> hitch, and `` formed a close friendship wich never entirely broke up.'' His favorite bit of <PERSON> Heinlein </PERSON> writing was the opening to `` Door Into Summer,'' in which `` he described a cat better than anyone has ever described a cat. The work that impressed me the most was ` Solution Unsatisfactory,' written before the <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> Project, in which he accurately described the current nuclear stalemate.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Anson </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinlein </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Butler </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, on July 7, 1907. He graduated from the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> and served for five years, but was forced to retire after contracting tuberculosis. Flat broke after a failed campaign for the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> legislature in 1938, <PERSON> Heinlein </PERSON> saw an ad in Thrilling Wonder Stories magazine offering a $ 50 prize for a story by an amateur. Instead of entering that contest, <PERSON> Heinlein </PERSON> sent his first story to Astounding Science Fiction magazine, which paid him $ 70. His books were written in a spare, matter-of-fact style but presented readers with thoughtful questions about how life should be lived. In his most popular novel, `` Stranger in a Strange Land,'' Valentine <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> is a human raised by Martians. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> challenged his home planet's values with his own priorities, including universal free love, nudity and many sexual encounters. He also `` discorporated'' or made disappear authority figures he felt were bad. The book, which became something of a text for the counter-culture of the 1960s, introduced `` grok,'' <PERSON> Heinlein </PERSON>'s word for intuitive understanding. In that book, <PERSON> Heinlein </PERSON> also introduced the water bed. In `` Methuselah's Children'' and later in other books, character Lazarus Long provides more food for thought. For instance, on how to get help, Long says: `` Never appeal to a man's better nature. He may not have one. Invoking his self-interest gives you more leverage.'' Another <PERSON> Heinlein </PERSON> invention, now in common use worldwide, is a device known as a `` waldo,'' named for the principal character in the short story, `` Magic, Inc.'' <PERSON> Waldo </PERSON>, who was handicapped, invented remote-controlled robot arms. Two years ago, <PERSON> Heinlein </PERSON> told writer <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> that `` writers do n't know how to retire.'' `` The bottom line,'' he said then, `` is ` pay to the order of ...' with the right figures in the blanks. That's the most important measure of a writer's work. Freelance writing is free enterprise.'' <PERSON> Heinlein </PERSON> won numerous awards for his novels and short stories and was popular with both children and adults, and he was not at all ashamed that much of his work was for `` pulp'' magazines, under his own name or pseudonyms. `` They did n't want it good,'' <PERSON> Heinlein </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> in 1980, `` they wanted it Wednesday.'' <PERSON> Heinlein </PERSON> won the Best Science Fiction Novel award from the World Science Fiction Convention in 1956, 1959, 1961 and 1966; the Nebula award from the Science Fiction Writers of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in 1975; and an unprecedented four Hugo awards, in 1956 for `` Double Star,'' in 1959 for `` Starship Troopers,'' in 1961 for `` Stranger in a Strange Land'' and in 1966 for `` The Moon is a Harsh Mistress.'' Other works include `` The <LOCATION> Green </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> of Earth'' and `` Puppet Masters.'' <PERSON> Heinlein </PERSON> is survived by his wife, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, whom he married in 1948. The couple had no children.
