<HEAD>Lawyers for Hakim, Secord, Drop Insistence on Seeing Ultra-Secret
Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The defense has removed a minor obstacle to the review of classified documents in the Iran-Contra conspiracy case, according to a transcript of a closed court hearing released Monday. Retired Marine Lt. Col. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> and former national security adviser <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> and their lawyers will review a small group of ultra-sensitive documents that government security officials were reluctant to show to arms dealers <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> and retired <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Secord </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> is allowing the defense to review the material to verify prosecution claims it is not relevant to charges that the four defendants conspired to illegally divert profits from the U.S.-Iran arms sales to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels. `` We do n't want to be viewed as obstructing this process,'' <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON>'s lawyer <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Janis </PERSON> told <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON>, according to the official court transcript of Friday's closed hearing <PERSON> Janis </PERSON> said he and <PERSON> Secord </PERSON>'s lawyer, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON>, agreed to abide by the determination of the other defense lawyers that the documents are not relevant to the case. Independent counsel <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> estimated that between 35 and 70 pages of sensitive material not relevant to the case have been identified by his office and government security experts. The defense concession does not dispose of the larger problem of disclosing sensitive information that may be determined to be relevant when the case goes to trial. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> issued an order Monday giving <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> until May 30 to draw up a list of secret documents he wants to use as evidence that wo n't be declassified by the government. Under the Classified Information Procedures Act, only the government can declassify documents before they are introduced into evidence. If <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> is unable to persuade government agencies to declassify important evidence, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> could drop some or all of the charges. No trial date has been set. At a hearing two weeks ago, <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> described some of the most sensitive documents in his possession as containing information about <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence and military planning. The disclosure of some secrets could subject some people in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> to torture or death, <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> had said, apparently referring to hostages held there. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> has ruled that each defendant has the right to examine the classified material that <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> has deposited in a secure facility where the defense lawyers are sifting through a massive amount of classified documents compiled by the prosecution. But government security officials have refused <PERSON> Secord </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> access because the material contains a small number of pages of ultra-sensitive material. <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON>, an Iranian-born <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen, has never had a security clearance and <PERSON> Secord </PERSON> has not had one since he left government several years ago. An interdepartmental task force is reviewing some 300,000 pages of classified material. More than 105,000 pages of documents have already been put in the secure room that was constructed by the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>.
