<HEAD>Queen Opens New Parliament Building; Aborigines Protest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> presided Monday at the opening of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s new <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, which took nearly $ 1 billion and eight years to build. About 2,000 aborigines protested outside. The British queen called the building a crowning expression of Australian faith in parliamentary democracy and noted that it replaces a provisional <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> building opened 61 years earlier by her father, King <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> VI </PERSON>. Aboriginal activists and sympathizers began gathering at dawn to protest the proceedings and their number grew to about 2,000 by the time the queen arrived. Chants of `` Shame, shame, shame!'' and `` We want land rights now!'' virtually drowned out the national anthem `` Advance Australia Fair'' during welcoming ceremonies attended by Prime Minister <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawke </PERSON> and other dignitaries. <PERSON> Robyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Dass </PERSON>, an aboriginal activist, said the new building is on a site sacred to the aborigines. Police said cables of the outdoor public address system were cut before the queen arrived but were restored about 10 minutes into the ceremony. The opening of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> is a highlight of year-long celebrations of the 200th anniversary of the European settlement of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. At a final cost of $ 1.1 billion -LRB- $ 836 million <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -RRB-, it also is the nation's most expensive building. There is enough concrete in it to build 25 replicas of <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>'s landmark Opera House. Opening it was <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON>'s last official function of a three-week tour that was her 11th visit to the country as queen. Huge crowds welcomed her and her husband, Prince <PERSON> Philip </PERSON>. The aborigin