with truce committees in action. Picks up 8th graf pvs, Lebanon's
1.2 ... with minor editing</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rival militias fought hand-to-hand Monday for control of Shiite slums and rained shells on each other's positions in the grim shantytowns despite Syrian army orders to stop the four days of carnage Police said 65 people were killed and 150 wounded Monday, bringing total casualties in the <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> territorial war to 154 dead and 367 wounded. The thunder of shellfire rolled over the city all day and into the night. Gunmen atop racing ambulances fired into the air to clear traffic so the wounded could reach hospitals. Radio stations appealed for blood donations. Doctors confirmed allegations by both sides that wounded fighters were dragged from ambulances and hospitals and slaughtered by their rivals. Fighting began Friday between the moderate militia Amal, which means <PERSON> Hope </PERSON> and has <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s backing, and the radical, pro-Iranian <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> has 25,000 soldiers in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, about 7,500 in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. It is the main power broker after 13 years of civil war but is being challenged by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which the Syrians support in its 8-year-old war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. The battle for control of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s southern slums, where an estimated 250,000 Shiites live, raised fears about the fate of 18 foreign hostages. They include nine Americans and most are believed held by Hezbollah-affiliated kidnappers in the 16-square-mile Shiite enclave. Late Monday, six committees, each grouping a Syrian officer, an Iranian Embassy official, a representative of Amal and one from <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, were formed and charged with enforcing a cease-fire. Fighting eased as the committees drove into the slums, but sporadic bursts of cannon and machine-gun fire echoed in the region well into the night. <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s 1.2 million Shiites are its largest sect. With <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s blessing, <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> crushed <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> last month in predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> The four-day battle cost 62 lives and 150 people were wounded. Among Monday's victims were three Amal militiamen killed with axes. Their bodies were taken to <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. Officials there said it was full to capacity and could not handle more casualties. An Amal spokesman said privately the three `` were axed to death after they were taken prisoner by <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>.'' Brig. Gen. <PERSON> Ghazi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenaan </PERSON>, Syrian military intelligence chief in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, said he told both factions to stop fighting. `` It is impermissible to let the current state of affairs continue,'' he told reporters after meetings with government, religious and militia leaders. Asked whether Syrian troops would intervene, he said: `` We hope it wo n't come to that, but we shall not allow the bloodshed to continue.'' <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> moved 7,500 soldiers into Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> in February 1987 to end a monthslong power struggle between Amal, led by Justice Minister <PERSON> Nabih </PERSON> <PERSON> Berri </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Walid </PERSON> <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON>'s Druse militia. Senior Moslem clerics urged <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> to repeat in the southern slums `` the successful west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> experiment of the past year.'' Gun battles were reported in al-Sahel Hospital. A doctor said some militiamen forced surgeons at gunpoint to operate on dead comrades `` to bring them to life.'' An <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> employee said: `` We take only victims needing emergency surgery, then send them to recuperate'' at inadequately equipped clinics in Druse-held mountains outside <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. Police said <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> fighters, wearing red headbands, appeared to have gained ground Monday in the densely populated <PERSON> Ghobeiri </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Bir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> el-Abed </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Hay </PERSON> <PERSON> Madi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mesharafieh </PERSON> districts. <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION>'s fighters, whose headbands are green or black, control most of Haret Hreik, Mreiji, <PERSON> Roweiss </PERSON>, <PERSON> Shiyah </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kasskass </PERSON>, a police spokesman said. `` <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> has established control over half of the slums,'' he said. `` It only controlled one-third before the current fighting.'' The spokesman, whose name can not be used because of regulations, said <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> had an advantage because it and the Syrians control entrances to the slums. `` This is <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION>'s trump card,'' he said. `` It can move in supplies and reinforcements from several other areas at will, while <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> can not get a fly in or out.'' An Amal fighter in the <LOCATION> Shiyah </LOCATION> district, <PERSON> Tarek </PERSON> <PERSON> Saad </PERSON>, aimed his shoulder-fired rocket launcher toward <PERSON> Hay </PERSON> <PERSON> Madi </PERSON> and said to reporters: `` God willing, we will liberate <PERSON> Hay </PERSON> <PERSON> Madi </PERSON> and Bir el-Abed and free all the foreign hostages. We know they are imprisoned there.'' There has been no word on the hostages since the fighting began. Police said about half the slum residents had fled to west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, camping on sidewalks or taking refuge in mosques, sports stadiums or schools. <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Kurdi </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> photo technician, was trapped with his wife and six children Friday in a shelter in <LOCATION> Bir </LOCATION> <LOCATION> el-Abed </LOCATION>, but escaped Monday. `` Shells rained nonstop around us,'' he said. `` Kids screamed and there was no way to comfort them or feed them.'' When fighting abated for a short time Monday, <PERSON> Kurdi </PERSON> said, `` I told my wife ` This is our chance to get out.' We did, dodging sniper fire as we ran out of Bir el-Abed.''
