<HEAD>Sikhs, Security Forces Battle at Golden Temple; 5 Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-2 ... CORRECTING in 2nd graf from Tuesday to
Monday. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, Militants began ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY27</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 2,500 government troops Monday fought a gun battle with extremists inside <LOCATION> Sikhism </LOCATION>'s holiest shrine and sealed off the temple. Police said at least five people were killed and five others wounded. Witnesses said the fighting continued late Monday. Militants began shooting from the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> after they spotted officers inspecting their positions from outside the temple. Security forces fired back with light machine guns, said <PERSON> Baldev </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, superintendent of police in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>. Sikh radicals have used the complex as a haven before. In June 1984, the army raided it. More than 1,200 people, mostly Sikhs, were killed. Less than four months later, Prime Minister <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> was assassinated by two of her Sikh bodyguards, setting off anti-Sikh riots in which more than 2,000 people were killed. On Monday, <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> district police chief <PERSON> Suresh </PERSON> <PERSON> Arona </PERSON> said two civilians and three suspected militants were seen lying in and near the shrine. One of the civilians, a woman, identified as <PERSON> Dilip </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaur </PERSON>, an 80-year-old Sikh, later died in a hospital. <PERSON> Venod </PERSON> <PERSON> Kumar </PERSON>, 30, a Hindu who worked with the local <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, was killed when he was caught in the crossfire just outside the main entrance of the temple, police said. Authorities imposed an indefinite curfew on the walled central district of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> to keep civilians indoors. Extremists have been fighting since 1982 for a separate Sikh nation in the northern agricultural province of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, and thousands of people have been killed. Sikhs make up less than 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million people but are a majority in The Sikh religion was founded five centuries ago as an alternative to <LOCATION> Hinduism </LOCATION> and Islam. Sikhs claim Hindus, the vast majority in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, discriminate against them. Also Monday, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported that five people were killed by Sikh extremists in overnight attacks elsewhere in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. On Saturday, Sikh gunmen killed 13 Hindu migrant workers at a wedding party in neighboring <LOCATION> Haryana </LOCATION> state. At least 941 people have been reported slain so far this year _ more than twice the rate in 1987, when Sikh extremists killed 1,000 people. Most victims were Hindus or moderate Sikhs. A government statement released Monday in <LOCATION> Chandigarh </LOCATION>, capital of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, called the shooting from inside the Golden Temple a `` great provocation.'' At the shrine, troopers sealed off exits and kept people from entering. `` We may have to take drastic action against the terrorists. We are watching,'' <PERSON> Arora </PERSON> said. Among Monday's injured was <PERSON> S.S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Virk </PERSON>, deputy inspector-general of the paramilitary <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, authorities said. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Virk </PERSON>, a Sikh, was out of danger after surgery for a bullet wound in the chin. He and other senior security officers had gone to posts on rooftops near the Golden Temple to look at a bunker Sikh militants were building at the western end of the complex, police reported. They said gunfire came from at least 16 points in the temple complex, mainly from Chinese-made AK-47 assault rifles. Violence has increased since <PERSON> Jasbir </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> <PERSON> Rode </PERSON> was made the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>'s chief priest early in March. He had been jailed under government anti-terrorism rules but released in an effort by Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, the late leader's son, to placate Sikh extremists and encourage them to negotiate. Since Rode's return, there have been persistent reports that the radicals were building bunkers and firing ports in the complex. <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> residents said they heard midnight target-practice sessions in the shrine.
