eling his book as a product of `` vindictiveness and revenge,'' <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> responded in an <ORGANIZATION> NBC-TV </ORGANIZATION> interview, `` They ought to know it when they see it.'' White House officials have acknowledged Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s interest in astrology, which it said was heightened in the aftermath of the March 30, 1981, assassination attempt on <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. But the officials never have conceded that astrology was a factor in setting <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s schedule _ as <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> alleges in his book. As some contents of the book became public late last week, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> emphatically denied that astrology played any role in policy decisions. At the conclusion of a Rose Garden ceremony Monday honoring small business executives, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was asked whether astrology played any role in the making of his schedule. `` It ca n't, because it never has,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> quickly told reporters the president had misunderstood the question, and had thought he was being asked the more general question of astrology's role in policy decisions. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s answer, the spokesman said, should be taken as a reiteration of the president's statement of last Friday, in which <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> denied using stargazing in the decision-making process. Earlier, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> was pressed during a news briefing to say whether astrology still plays a role in deciding the president's schedule and public appearances Both <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> and <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Crispen </PERSON>, the first lady's press secretary, said Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will continue to consult with an astrologist, who has been identified as <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> socialite <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quiqley </PERSON>. `` She does n't plan to stop talking to her,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Crispen </PERSON> said. She said these conversations will take place on an `` as-needed basis. ... It's not a daily, weekly, type of thing.'' An administration official, discussing the atmosphere at the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on grounds he remain unidentified, said `` I'm not noticing any disruptions'' as a result of the furor over the <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> book. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> denied that the brouhaha was adversely affecting <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s ability to perform. `` The president's management style and his personal methods of leadership and management have been discussed in any number of forums,'' the spokesman said. `` The bottom line is that they work.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>'s predecessor, <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON>, who touched off a furor with his earlier book acknowledging that he had fabricated quotes in <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s name, said Monday he had some qualms about the newest revelations. `` Who's to say his style is n't the best,'' <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> said in a Cable News Network interview. `` He had a good grip on the presidency. He managed it just right and it worked well with one notable exception _ Iran-Contra.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> repeatedly suggested that reporters were blowing the stargazing matter out of proportion. `` Why does every newspaper in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> carry a horoscope? Does every editor and publisher think it's unwieldy? As a personal comfort, millions of people look to astrology,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. The Rev. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Falwell </PERSON>, a staunch <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> political supporter, expressed dismay over the allegations in the <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> book. `` I'm sincerely hopeful that Mr. <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> was exaggerating or misstating the facts,'' <PERSON> Falwell </PERSON> said in a statement issued by his office. `` As one who believes in God as the creator of the universe, it is incomprehensible to me to think of consulting the stars rather than their maker,'' he said. `` A belief in God and a belief in astrology can not be reconciled.''
