<HEAD>Most-Wanted Military Fugitive Returned For Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: 4 grafs SUB for grafs 5-7 pvs, Officials said ... UPDATING
with prosecutor's later remarks. Pick up 8th graf pvs, Jensen ruled
...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s most-wanted military fugitive, cashiered Army Gen. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, came home in handcuffs Monday to face 39 murder charges linked to <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s `` dirty war'' against leftists Extradited by a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, the balding, stocky ex-general arrived aboard a regular flight of <ORGANIZATION> Aerolineas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Argentinas </ORGANIZATION>, the Argentine airline, from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The plane was stopped 300 yards from the airport terminal and <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, dressed in gray slacks, a sweater and white tennis shoes, was removed and placed aboard an armored prisoner-transport vehicle. Escorted by three police cars, an armored car and an ambulance, the ex-general was taken first to <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Headquarters </ORGANIZATION> in downtown <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>, then removed to a special top-security jail and finally placed in a small cell, reserved for prisoners facing trial, at the somber Federal Court Building. Federal Prosecutor <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> <PERSON> Ocampo </PERSON> said <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, 64, would be held `` in isolation'' there until questioning later this week by federal judges. `` We also have to wait for the official translation of the sentence dictated by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Judge <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Jensen </PERSON>,'' who ordered <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s extradition on April 27 after 15 months of hearings in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> <PERSON> Ocampo </PERSON> said. He said, `` I am going to request a life sentence ... -LRB- the maximum -RRB- and he will be sentenced to life.'' <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> <PERSON> Ocampo </PERSON> predicted the trial could begin `` in late July or the beginning of August.'' <PERSON> Jensen </PERSON> ruled that <PERSON> Suarz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, who fled <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> in 1984 and was arrested by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> marshals in January, 1987 in a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francicco </LOCATION> suburb, could be tried in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> on charges of 39 murders, allegedly conducted by troops under his command. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, supporting its case with 1,600 pages of documents, had sought <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s extradition on 43 charges of murder as well as other crimes. He had been accused in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> in 635 separate cases of human rights violations as well as misappropriation of more than $ 2 million in government funds. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> judge rejected four of the murder charges, ruling that identification of the victims was inadequate, approved a charge of forging a passport renewal, and also rejected 23 kidnapping charges, saying the five-year legal deadline for filing the charges had expired in 1984. Under extradition law, <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> can be tried only on charges for which extradition was approved. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s trial had been personally ordered by President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> shortly after the civilian president took office in December 1983, ending nearly eight years of rightist military rule. The former commander of the Buenos Aires-based 1st <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>, was stripped of rank and pension in April 1984, after being declared `` in rebellion'' for ignoring repeated summonses to appear for questioning in connection with the abduction, torture and murder of suspected leftists in the late 1970s. A government-appointed commission has reported that at least 9,000 Argentines disappeared in the `` dirty war'' against leftist subversives waged by the armed forces regime that seized power in 1976 after ousting former President <PERSON> Isabel </PERSON> <PERSON> Peron </PERSON>. From 1976 to 1978, <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> commanded the <ORGANIZATION> 1st </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>, in whose area more than half of the disappearances took place. Then he was named head of the Joint Chief of Staff. When he retired in 1981, he was named president of the huge state oil monopoly <ORGANIZATION> Yacimientos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroliferos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fiscales </ORGANIZATION>, a post he held until 1982. The misappropriation of government funds charge is linked to <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s period as head of the oil company. In other trials ordered by <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>, five former ruling junta members, including two ex-presidents, were convicted in December 1985 of human rights offenses and sentenced to prison terms ranging from life to four years. They now are serving their terms at a military prison. The Argentine <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last May approved a so-called `` law of due obedience,'' which absolved most of the more than 300 military officers from trial on rights abuse charges on grounds that they were following orders from superiors. The law did not absolve high-ranking officers who directed the anti-subversive campaign.
