<HEAD>Hail Peppers Michigan, Ohio Valley</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Thunderstorms developed Monday over lower <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> and western <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, producing hail in many communities, while other parts of the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> had rain and gusty winds. One-inch-diameter hail was reported in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> west of <LOCATION> Greensburg </LOCATION>, at <LOCATION> Warren </LOCATION> and north of <LOCATION> Batesville </LOCATION>. Hail the size of quarters fell in parts of <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, in east-central <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, and southwest of <LOCATION> Muncie </LOCATION>. Nickel-sized hail fell near <LOCATION> Napoleon </LOCATION> in northwest <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, and dime-sized hail was reported near <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION> in west-central <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. Reports of pea - to marble-sized hail were received from across much of southern <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> A resident of <LOCATION> Buchanan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bend </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, reported his yard was covered with half-inch-diameter hail late Monday morning. A thunderstorm at <LOCATION> Haggerstown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, was accompanied by 50 mph winds, small hail and heavy rain. Tornado watches were in effect until Monday evening for southeast lower <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, most of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, southeast <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> and north-central <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>. On Sunday as many as 82 tornadoes swept through the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. There were few injuries, but one man was killed when high wind collapsed a building under construction in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. Elsewhere, Monday, showers fell from western <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> across western <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and <LOC