<FIRST>r i Panama-US     05-09 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>Panama-US,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ambassador Ordered Chartered Plane to Military Airport</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ambassador <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> ordered his chartered Panamanian plane to leave a civilian airport and fly to a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> air base because he was concerned for his safety, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. It said <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> made the decision Sunday afternoon when he saw Panamanian security men arguing with his own security detail after the plane landed at the small civilian Paitilla airport. `` It was a judgment call,'' an embassy statement said. `` The ambassador's security detail made the judgment that the -LRB- situation at <LOCATION> Paitilla </LOCATION> -RRB- was not a good environment.'' Maj. <PERSON> Pascual </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Panamanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, called it a hijacking incident. He said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials refused to provide any information about the plane after it landed at <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in the former <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> Canal Zone about five miles from <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. It was the second apparent attempt by <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> security to interfere with the ambassador's movements. On April 3, a military vehicle tried to stop his limousine as he left the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> ambassador's residence. Relations between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> have been difficult since the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration began supporting efforts to oust Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> as commander of the Defense Forces and the power behind the civilian government. A federal court in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> indicted <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> in February on drug trafficking charges. After <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> had the legislature dismiss President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> on Feb. 26, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> began imposing financial sanctions on <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> had tried to fire the general as military commander the day before. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> still recognizes <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> as president. Banks began cashing checks and permitting withdrawals Monday for the first time in more than two months, with strict limits on the amount to be taken out of an account. No withdrawals had been allowed since March 3, longer at some banks, because of runs on deposits and cash shortages. New rules limit withdrawals from checking accounts to 25 percent of the March 3 balance, to a maximum of $ 10,000. Some banks began taking deposits April 18 and performing some other operations a week later. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, director of the aeronautics board, told a news conference `` procedures'' were required for a civilian aircraft to land at a military base and spend the night there. He said the plane chartered by the embassy group, a six-seat <PERSON> Piper </PERSON>, did not follow them. The embassy statement said `` the ambassador considered it an emergency,'' and ordered the pilot to take off from the civilian airport for nearby <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>. Embassy officials would not say who else was on the plane. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> and his party were returning from a day at the Contadora resort island. According to <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, others on the plane included <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> Galindo </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, son-in-law of <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>, who is in hiding in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, and the son of an opposition leader. He said the incident started when airport security personnel saw four `` armed men on the restricted grounds.'' He said airport security questioned them and identified them as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens. `` It was then that the plane landed,'' he said, adding that embassy security men talked to the ambassador on the radio and the plane took off. The embassy said <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> security men were armed with M-16 rifles and shotguns, demanded passports and other documents and `` their manner was considered hostile.'' `` As far as we are concerned, until we conclude the investigation, the plane was hijacked or stolen,'' <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> said. The plane's owner, <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Giraud </PERSON>, attended the news conference with the major and said the embassy had not informed him his plane was at <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>. A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> official said the aircraft remained there because `` a new flight plan must be filed'' before it could be flown out.
