of <LOCATION> Addam </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Swapp </LOCATION>. While admitting that Mrs. Singer my not have directly participated in crimes, prosecutors charged her with the most counts, alleging her aiding and abetting of family members made her just as culpable. `` She was n't exactly sitting back in a rocking chair in her bedroom crocheting and reading Scriptures,'' <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said. Clan members maintained the bombing and standoff were ordered by <PERSON> God </PERSON> as a sign of the impending collapse of church, state and nation, but also were intended to draw attention to the 1979 slaying of polygamist patriarch <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>, Mrs. Singer's husband and <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>'s father-in-law. Singer was shot following an 18-day standoff at the same farm by authorities trying to arrest him on warrants stemming from his refusal to send his children to public schools and his defiance of a court order that he relinquish the children of his second wife to their father. The family contended Singer was murdered in a `` church-state conspiracy.'' `` I guess you could say it started back in 1973 when <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON> took his children out of public schools,'' Addam Swapp testified.
