<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> began a tour of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s poorest country Monday with an appeal to its people `` not to lose hope.'' `` I will spend five days among you, sharing your aspirations, seeing first-hand this nation stricken by poverty and a lack of development and resources,'' he said in an arrival speech at the <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paz </LOCATION> <LOCATION> airport </LOCATION>, which is 13,150 feet above sea level and ringed by snow-capped Andean peaks. President <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> <PERSON> Estenssoro </PERSON> said in a welcoming speech the visit would help bolster the flagging spirits of Bolivians. `` You come at a time when <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> is suffering bitter tests that could weaken its spirit or perhaps sink it into a state of desperation,'' the 80-year-old president said. He said technological and scientific advances had heightened aspirations of the Third World without providing the means to fulfill them. `` The <LOCATION> Bolivian </LOCATION> people have perhaps been more harshly punished than most in this respect,'' he said, Thousands of people, including many peasants in colorful Indian dress and traditional bowler hats, greeted the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> leader at the airport. He arrived from <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> on a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 of the state airline <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aereo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boliviano </ORGANIZATION> at 5:16 p.m. The pontiff, a skier, spoke in a strong voice and showed no outward signs of being affected by altitude sickness, which Bolivians call `` sorocche.'' <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> is the world's highest capital and the altitude makes many visitors uncomfortable, if not ill. However, in a meeting with <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>'s 39 bishops at the end of the day, the pope seemed to be wearying. Bishop <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Terrazas </PERSON>, head of the local episcopal conference, did not deliver a prepared speech to the pontiff because `` we see that the pope is tired.'' `` I believe these words have no place right now because of the weariness that your first day here has caused to the Holy Father,'' <PERSON> Terrazas </PERSON> said to the pope. He instead handed the pope a copy of the speech. In the text of <PERSON> Terrazas </PERSON>' speech, he told the pope <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> suffers from `` a situation of injustice that consumes thousands of brothers in degrading misery and inhumane unemployment. To this are added other ills such as delinquency, immorality and drug trafficking and other social calamaities that constitute a devastating scourge to the very being of our people.'' The pope was spending the night in the papal nuncio's residence. Dealers in compressed oxygen said church officials rented several tanks and face-masks for use if needed by the papal entourage. To review the military honor guard and groups of white-smocked schoolgirls at the airport, the pope rode in a green army jeep rather than taking the long walk. From the airport the papal caravan descended to <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paz </LOCATION>, which is 11,930 feet above the sea in a mountain ravine. The vehicles moved down a cliffside highway that was lined by tens of thousands of people. Crowds cheered and waved banners of yellow and white, the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> colors, and the yellow, red and green Bolivian flag. Peasant shacks perched precariously on the mountainsides were brilliant white, freshly painted by their owners. The city government offered special tax incentives to those who painted their homes. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, standing in the glass booth of the popemobile, traveled 11 miles through the city center to the papal nuncio's residence, where he is staying He will spend five days in <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, the second and longest stop on his four-nation tour, which began Friday in <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> and will include visits to <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION>. He returns to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> on May 18. The pontiff will visit seven Bolivian cities ranging from the tin mining center of <LOCATION> Oruro </LOCATION>, devastated by mine closures, to the lowland boom town of <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cruz </LOCATION>, a center of cattle ranching, agriculture and cocaine trafficking. Government austerity measures eliminated an annual inflation rate of 20,000 percent in <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, but they caused serious labor unrest because of mass layoffs. The country is also a major source of coca leaves, the raw material for cocaine. This visit is the <PERSON> pope </PERSON>'s tour ninth to <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> since he became head of the 860-million-member <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> nearly 10 years ago. He has made 37 pilgrimages abroad from the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> is scheduled to spend his 68th birthday in <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION> on May 18.
