UPDATE with statement from National Education Association</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, a scourge of school bureaucrats, teacher unions and slipshod standards during 3 -LCB- years as secretary of education, said Monday he will resign his <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> post in mid-September to return to private life. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> made the announcement after <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> met privately with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> at the White House and then informed his senior staff of his departure plans. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> told the staff he had recommended that <PERSON> Linus </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, the undersecretary of education and a former superintendent of schools in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, succeed him. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> told education reporters last month he probably would not stay for the final few months of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. In somewhat uncharacteristic fashion, he refused to take calls from reporters Monday to discuss his plans, which include hitting the lecture circuit and writing a book spelling out his vision for improving <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s schools and colleges. His spokesman, <PERSON> Loye </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, read this terse statement: `` Secretary <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> met today with the president and subsequently with <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> staff to say that he intends to leave his position in mid-September. He expressed his gratitude to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> for the opportunity to serve in his Cabinet. The secretary reiterated to his staff his intention to continue at ` full speed ahead' during the next few months.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> plans to issue two new reports on a model elementary school curriculum and on improving colleges before he steps down, said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Kristol </PERSON>, his chief of staff. The college book will try `` to shed some light on the black box of higher education'' with practical advice for parents, policy-makers and others, he said. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> made headlines throughout his tenure with acerbic criticisms of teacher unions, the `` blob'' of school bureaucracy, the `` greed'' of colleges raising tuitions twice as fast as inflation, and the `` <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Crow </PERSON> math and back-of-the-bus science'' meted out to black children in ghetto schools. He called <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s schools the nation's worst and said that system was in an `` educational meltdown. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement Monday that it wishes <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> well and and expressed hope that the next secretary of education `` will use the power of the office to be a positive force in support of public education.'' `` The nation needs a secretary of education who will work cooperatively with parents, teachers, school administrators, college faculty and the community at large,'' the <ORGANIZATION> NEA </ORGANIZATION> statement said. Two weeks ago, in a report called, `` American Education: Making It Work,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> warned that the public has little to show for five years of school reform. The schools are `` slightly improved,'' he said, but `` we are certainly not doing well enough, and we are not doing well enough fast enough.'' He called for using the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military to wage war against drug traffickers, and quarreled with the surgeon general over what to teach children about AIDS and condoms. His penchant for controversy was evident from his first news conference in 1985, when he suggested that college students cope with aid cuts through `` stereo divestiture, automobile divestiture, three-weeks-at-the-beach divestiture.'' The remark drew howls from outraged college administrators _ and tongue-in-cheek ripostes from collegians on spring break in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, 44, championed what he called `` the three C's'' of education: choice, character and content He failed to convince <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to offer poor parents vouchers to buy remedial education at either public or private schools. But his criticism of bilingual education led <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to ease restrictions on aid for English-immersion programs. He argued strenuously that teachers had a duty to impart strong morals to their students. And, as with his attack on `` <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Crow </PERSON> math,'' he insisted that tough, unyielding standards _ such as those he outlined in a model curriculum called `` <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Madison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>'' _ were essential for all children. He said the civil rights challenge of the 1990s was to `` ensure equal intellectual opportunity'' in school. He was an unapologetic defender of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> efforts to slash the federal education budget, arguing that more money did not guarantee better results and that state and local school budgets were rising inexorably anyway. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> has been a peripatetic Cabinet officer, visiting nearly 100 elementary and secondary schools. He has also proven a big draw as an after-dinner speaker on the Republican fund-raising circuit. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, who switched from the Democratic to the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> two years ago, has spoken at 63 <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> functions in the past three years, according to the trade publication Education Week. There has been speculation that <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> may eventually run for office, possibly from his adopted state of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>.
