<HEAD>Glasnost Debated At IPI Meeting Attended by Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMEL ANIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet journalists debated the meaning and the future of glasnost with their Western colleagues Monday at the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>'s annual meeting. This was the first IPI general assembly attended by Soviet and Chinese representatives. About 400 publishers and editors from 43 countries are taking part in the <ORGANIZATION> IPI </ORGANIZATION> assembly. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Pumpyansky </PERSON>, editor in chief of the Soviet weekly <PERSON> Novoe </PERSON> <PERSON> Vremia </PERSON>, described Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of glasnost _ or greater openness on certain issues in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> society _ as realism, `` seeing the world as it is, not in ideological dogmas.'' Delegates laughed and applauded when he added, `` It is like in the fairy tale when the little child says the king has no clothes... or badly dressed if dressed in a Soviet suit. <PERSON> Conor </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruise </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Dublin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> said forces exist in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> that want to reduce the substance of glasnost. He said the policy would have a better chance for success if confined to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Developments in other <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact countries could prove to be the `` Achilles heel'' of glasnost, letting loose revolutionary forces, <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> stated. `` There are ominous signs in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>,'' he said. <PERSON> Pierro </PERSON> <PERSON> Ottone </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Repubblica </ORGANIZATION> said glasnost should be viewed as the instrument of a power struggle in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> as a new class wants to get rid of the old mentality in search of a pragmatic solution to Soviet problems. `` There could be unpredictable consequences of this struggle,'' <PERSON> Ottone </PERSON> said. He said it could let loose tensions not only in the other <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact countries but in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> as well, citing recent Armenian unrest as an example. In Monday's opening ceremony of the general assembly, <ORGANIZATION> IPI </ORGANIZATION> officials demanded a lifting of restrictions on the press in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> IPI </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Galliner </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> had made significant progress in restoring democracy since the return to civilian rule in 1983. But he said a constant threat to the news media exists from legislation providing for prosecution and imprisonment of journalists and hefty fines for publications deemed pornographic. The publishers and editors of two men's magazines, <LOCATION> Playboy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bravo </LOCATION>, were fined a total of $ 750,000 on Dec. 10 The fines have not yet been paid, and the government has announced plans for legislation to substantially reduce the fines. <PERSON> Galliner </PERSON> also noted that state-produced newsprint prices have gone up 200 percent in the past 16 months. He and <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Cebrian </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> IPI </ORGANIZATION> board chairman, appealed for an amnesty for political prisoners jailed during military rule in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> and an end to prosecution of journalists for what they write. The <ORGANIZATION> IPI </ORGANIZATION>, an independent organization with offices in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, represents 2,000 publishers and editors in more than 60 countries and is dedicated to defending press freedom. The Turkish military took over in 1980, following widespread political violence which claimed 5,000 lives in the three years prior to the coup. The generals relinquished power after 1983 general elections won by the <ORGANIZATION> Motherland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> of Premier <PERSON> Turgut </PERSON> <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON>. Since return to civilian rule, no journalists have been imprisoned but several are on trial on charges of insulting the president or the premier or dealing with taboo subjects such as the problem of the Kurdish minority. <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> defended his pricing policies, saying state subsidies, including those on newsprint, were lifted as part of his program to establish a free-market economy in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. He conceded that a chief function of the press is criticism of the government but complained that `` a pervasive pessimism'' is spreading through the society because of too much negative news. <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON>, without citing specific examples, told the delegates that in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> `` people are shying away from a political career'' because of invasion of privacy. The premier recommended a peaceful approach in covering foreign news so not to fan hostilities among nations, especially with neighbors. On the agenda for the three-day meeting are, among other topics, problems on reporting from Islamic countries, protection of privacy and the future of <ORGANIZATION> UNESCO </ORGANIZATION>. END -LRB- EA -RRB-
