<HEAD>Jury Begins Deliberations in Scarfo Murder Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jury began deliberating the fate of reputed mob boss <PERSON> Nicodemo </PERSON> `` Little Nicky'' <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON> and eight associates Monday after hearing the prosecutor defend her two key witnesses in the murder case. The jury will return to the courtroom of Common Pleas Judge <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabo </PERSON> on Tuesday morning to continue deliberations. The 59-year-old <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON>, who police allege ran the area's Mafia from his home in <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, before his arrest in 1986, and the other eight defendants are charged with the Sept. 14, 1984, murder of rival <PERSON> Salvatore </PERSON> <PERSON> Testa </PERSON>. <PERSON> Testa </PERSON>'s body, with two bullets in the head, was found trussed with rope and wrapped in a blanket in a wooded area in <LOCATION> south </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. The trial began more than two months ago. Jury selection took more than four weeks, and the testimony phase took another month. Assistant District Attorney <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s 78-minute closing statement followed almost eight hours of defense arguments over two days last week and an hour Monday morning. She acknowledged that prosecution witnesses <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Caramandi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> DelGiorno </PERSON> were despicable men. `` Rats? Yes,'' Ms. <PERSON> Christie </PERSON> said. `` But when you enter a sewer do n't rats lead the way? ... `` DelGiorno and <PERSON> Caramandi </PERSON> told you that <PERSON> Nicky </PERSON> <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON> was the boss and that <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON>' organization eliminated problems and dissension by simple execution.'' Caramanda and <PERSON> DelGiorno </PERSON> testified <PERSON> Testa </PERSON> was murdered in a south <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> candy store, closed for renovations, and the body was