<FIRST>r i AM-SchizophrenicBrains     05-09 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Schizophrenic Brains,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abnormality in Schizophrenic Brains Pinpointed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A study of schizophrenics' brains suggests a possible answer to a decades-old mystery about an abnormality associated with the illness, a researcher said Monday. Brain scans of 17 living patients pinpointed a site of a reduction in brain tissue that apparently produces enlargement of normal brain cavities, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Suddath </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>. The enlargement of the fluid-filed spaces, called ventricles, had been observed since the 1930s, but nobody has known which part of the brain produces it, he said. Failure of part of the brain to develop, or shrinkage, could produce the enlargement, he said. If the new finding is confirmed, it points the way to an anatomical target for further study of schizophrenia, he said. <PERSON> Suddath </PERSON> spoke to reporters at the annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. He did the work with colleagues at the mental health institute. The brain scans, using a technique called magnetic resonance imaging, found an average of a 20 percent reduction in the gray matter of the temporal lobes, compared with the volume found in 17 normal people of similar age and size. The temporal lobes lie beneath the temples on each side of the head. The less temporal lobe gray matter a patient had, the larger his lateral ventricles tended to be, implicating that tissue was at least part of the explanation for enlargement of the ventricles, <PERSON> Suddath </PERSON> said. Researchers do not know when the reduction in gray matter appears in comparison to when schizophrenia appears, he said. It may be a failure of the tisue to develop before birth or around the time of birth, he said. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Freedman </PERSON>, director of the division of adult psychiatry at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Neuropsychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, noted that the study included few patients. `` It's too soon to say'' whether it will pay off in better diagnosis or predicting response to treatment, he said. But it is `` a promising start'' in using magnetic resonance imaging to seek clues to brain abnormalities in schizophrenia, he said.
</TEXT>
