for the ascent to offices above and below gutted floors 12 through 16. Many of the employees filled boxes, bags, suitcases and briefcases with files, computer disks and telephone lists. `` They had 15 minutes to select the things they need the most,'' said bank spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Popovich </PERSON>. He said the bank had gotten many of its employees back to work either in the undamaged parts of the building or in nearby leased space, thanks to an emergency plan designed for earthquakes. He said it would take 10 days to four weeks to clean up smoke and water damage, but there was no estimate on the time to rebuild the gutted floors. The fire department's preliminary estimate of $ 450 million was `` exceedingly high,'' <PERSON> Popovich </PERSON> said.
