<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, May 16, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Sudan Has Severe Problems after Two Years of Civilian Rule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Reminiscent of the 1970s oil crisis around the world, Sudanese wait in line these days as long as 12 hours for gasoline. Lines form as well for sugar, bread and other necessities in short supply. Two years after army generals gave power to Prime Minister <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> el-Mahdi </PERSON>, his civilian government is having to contend with a faltering economy and a costly war in the south. Inflation reaching 70 percent has sent prices soaring, and strikes are commonplace as workers try to deal with it. The war costs the government an estimated $ 1 million a day in borrowed money. <PERSON> El-Mahdi </PERSON> won national elections in April 1986, a year after the military overthrew <PERSON> Gaafar </PERSON> <PERSON> Nimeiri </PERSON>, the president for 16 years. But <PERSON> el-Mahdi </PERSON> sees a bright side to his two years as the nation's leader `` We have moved the country from a famine-stricken, collapsed economy to a working economy which is able to feed itself and which has resumed its contacts with the international community on an equitable and just basis,'' he said in an interview. Many Sudanese and foreign diplomats disagree. Sudanese joke about it: `` There's democracy, a lot of democracy, but that's about the only commodity available.'' Said a diplomat: `` In theory, if <PERSON> el-Mahdi </PERSON>'s government continues to drift with no firm program, that plus economic distress surely will affect the democratic process and increase the possibility of a military takeover. That's been the cycle historically.'' It has taken most of <PERSON> el-Mahdi </PERSON>'s time and all his political prowess in the last two years to maintain equilibrium among the country's 35 diverse political parties and 597 tribes. He fired his Cabinet on grounds of inefficiency in the spring of 1986, and the next one lasted less than a year. The crisis that followed remains unresolved as <PERSON> el-Mahdi </PERSON> seeks to put together and effective coalition of the five largest political parties _ a mixture of center-right, Moslem fundamentalists and non-Moslem southerners. The major stumbling block is finding alternatives to Islamic law that <PERSON> Nimeiri </PERSON> implemented in 1983. Although ignored since the 1985 coup, the law of Islam remain officially as <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s basic law. <PERSON> Nimeiri </PERSON> avoided economic problems by securing foreign loans. The <ORGANIZATION> Transitional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> that replaced him froze interest payments on those loans. <PERSON> El-Mahdi </PERSON>, whose government must deal with a $ 12-billion foreign debt, says his government ca n't be responsible for the mistakes of past leaders. That position enticed countries like <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> to write off <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s debts to them. But <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> is not likely to hold out much longer on the foreign aid it is now getting and foreign lenders are expected to extend more loans without some form of economic reform. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other foreign donors pour in $ 700 million to $ 800 million annually in cash, oil and other commodities. A Western economist estimated that <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> needs $ 1 billion to $ 1.5 billion a year for the next four years `` just to keep up its present position.'' The civil war in southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> is a constant financial drain, as is the huge public sector. For example, the government's railway corporation, which moves less than 10 percent of <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s freight, employs 370,000 people. It moved more than 80 percent of the freight 30 years ago with fewer than half as many people. Government sugar factories produce 600,000 tons of sugar a year, which should satisfy local annual consumption needs of 560,000 tons. Nevertheless, the government imports 200,000 tons a year because 250,000 tons of domestic sugar are smuggled to neighboring countries for higher prices. The International Monetary Fund and other lenders are calling <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> to cut back on such costly ways. The Oxford-educated <PERSON> el-Mahdi </PERSON> said in the interview that one of the first tasks once the new government is formed will be to adopt a four-year economic reform plan. It will include rehabilitation of agricultural, industrial and service institutions and the construction of new roads and dams, he said. Closely linked to the economic morass is the civil war in southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, where the rebel <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> has held the upper hand for almost a year, its first sustained success since the conflict began in 1983. The Ethiopian-backed rebels, mainly Christians and animists fighting the Moslem-dominated government in <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>, demand autonomy and a larger share of <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s assets for the southern zone. They also want Islamic law abrogated. The country is thought to have extensive oil reserves, mostly in the south, but the war prevents exploitation. Southern farms ca n't till their fertile fields because of the fighting and work has been halted on a major canal project, which if completed would divert Nile River water throughout <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, May 16</NOTE>
