<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 3 b&amp;w
photos.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ Despite being regarded as second-class citizens in most of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, women in the past three decades have emerged as powerful political leaders in several countries in the region. As one political scientist put it, `` I think there is a very strong substrata of matriarchy in the society.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Time after time, the scenario has been replayed in the Asian Subcontinent: the powerful leader falls, sometimes to an assassin's bullet, and beside the body is the grieving wife or daughter. Then, tears brushed away and replaced by determination, she picks up the mantle of power in a part of the world where many women still are sold into marriages or brothels, cast aside for failing to produce sons or consigned to lives of serving men. In the past three decades, several women have emerged as powerful political leaders in this way. They include: _ The late Prime Minister <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, rivaled by few men anywhere in the world for iron will and ability to leave an indelible stamp on the fabric of a nation _ <PERSON> Sirimavo </PERSON> <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, the world's first woman prime minister and a strong contender to govern her nation once again _ <PERSON> Benazir </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, head of the most visible opposition force confronting President <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> ul-Haq </PERSON> _ <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Hasina </PERSON> and <PERSON> Khaleda </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, leaders of the longest sustained opposition protests against any leader of their coup-prone country Each of them has handled power skillfully, although Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> and Mrs. <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON> were doomed by their excesses. Not one of them could be considered a feminist. Each pledged, at least in the beginning, to uphold the ideals of her late father or husband. `` The people feel that the wife is the best to carry on,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON> says during an interview in the colonnaded home in <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> where Prime Minister S.W.R.D. <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON> was gunned down by a <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monk in 1959. `` They trust the wife to carry on the husband's policies more than anyone else.'' The 72-year-old Mrs. <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON> pauses for a moment, then adds: `` There is a certain amount of sympathy for the widow. You ca n't deny that also helps.'' In Mrs. <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON>'s case, her husband's <ORGANIZATION> Sri </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lanka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> was in shambles after his death. The party's men squabbled for nearly a year, then enlisted her to restore unity. She served as prime minister from 1960 to 1965 and again from 1970 to 1977, when voters rebelled against tight economic controls that banned most imports and saw people standing in line for bread. Older and wiser, Mrs. <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON> is ready for office again, and is said to have a good chance of winning elections scheduled for 1989. President <PERSON> Junius </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON>, who defeated Mrs. <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON> in 1977, replaced the parliamentary system with a presidential one and is barred from seeking another term. His <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> is under attack for failing to end a four-year war by Tamil guerrillas against the Sinhalese ethnic majority. Mrs. <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON>, like the region's other powerful women, said her sex has not been an issue. Despite being second-class citizens in most South Asian societies, women have a `` market value in the political arena,'' says <PERSON> Ashis </PERSON> <PERSON> Nandy </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>'s Center for the Study of Developing Societies. `` I think there is a very strong substrata of matriarchy in the society,'' he says. It's a cultural phenomenon that transcends the region's dominant religions: <LOCATION> Hinduism </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, Buddhism in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> and Islam in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>. `` Traditionally, in all these societies, femininity has been associated with activism and power,'' says <PERSON> Nandy </PERSON>, who trained as a clinical psychologist before entering political science. He noted that <LOCATION> Hinduism </LOCATION>'s female deities invoke greater fear than male deities. Paintings of <PERSON> Krishna </PERSON> and other gods have a gentle, almost androgynous quality, while <PERSON> Kali </PERSON>, goddess of destruction, is drenched in blood with human heads hanging from her waist _ and is unmistakably female. `` The king of the gods is a man, but the crucial, powerful gods relevant to everyday life are women,'' <PERSON> Nandy </PERSON> says. `` Pestilence, health, child care, fertility: These are goddesses.'' <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, daughter of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s first prime minister, <PERSON> Jawaharlal </PERSON> <PERSON> Nehru </PERSON>, was known as `` Bharat Mhata,'' Mother of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. She was loved, hated, feared, but above all respected. She abolished the princely estates of the maharajahs, intervened in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s civil war to create the new nation of <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> in 1971 and led <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> into the nuclear age.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
