<NOTE>$adv22</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 5 b&amp;w
photos. ColorFoto subscribers get 2 35mm slides.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ Two questions. What was the first human transplant, and which is the most successful? The answer to both is the cornea, which gives sight to 35,000 people a year. The irony is that the very success of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s eye banks has caused their biggest frustration, a lack of donors.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JULES LOH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Their battle cry could properly be `` an eye for an eye.'' But there is no vengeance in the hearts of these crusaders, only mercy. They work in a small, quiet lab high above <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s blare and glare, and, with dawn-to-midnight effort, seem to be gaining on their quest: the gift of sight for all who can have it _ without delay. `` We're providing more corneas for transplant every year,'' says <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Dahl </PERSON>. `` Dramatically more in recent years, but still not enough. `` When I came here seven years ago the waiting period was four months. Now it's down to five weeks. The pity is that there should n't have to be any waiting time at all. The eyes are there, the donors are not.'' Ms. <PERSON> Dahl </PERSON> is the lab director for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Eye-Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Restoration </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. It is the nation's first and largest eye bank among the more than 100 throughout the nation. Last year it provided 1,400 corneas for transplant, all it could obtain, but, as Ms. <PERSON> Dahl </PERSON> said, not enough. The irony is that the very success of corneal transplants, the first human tissue transplanted successfully, is the eye bank's biggest problem `` The large organ transplants, the hearts, the kidneys, the lungs, are the ones that get all the publicity and national appeals for donors,'' says <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON>, the eye bank's executive director. `` Corneal transplants have become so commonplace people assume one will be available every time one is needed. That, of course, is far from the case.'' Since its beginning two generations ago, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s eye bank has provided corneas for 30,000 transplants. And, yes, the procedure has become so routine that that number now equals almost as many as are done in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> every year. On an average day in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, one heart, 20 kidneys and 65 corneas are transplanted _ one cornea every 22 minutes, more corneas than all other transplants combined. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> eye bank was established in 1944 by a pioneering physician, the late <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Townley </PERSON> <PERSON> Paton </PERSON>. He used eyes donated by consenting convicts on death row at Sing Sing Prison, just up the <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, and lost a housekeeper in the process when she opened the fridge one morning, saw two eyes in a saucer of liquid, and left. <PERSON> Paton </PERSON>, who died four years ago, wrote the first textbook published in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on corneal transplants, forerunner of all organ transplants. The cornea is not an organ. The eye is the organ, the cornea a tissue. At least at this stage doctors see no way the eye, once severed from the optic nerve, can ever be transplanted. The cornea is the transparent front surface of the eye, about the size and thickness of a dime. It is the window through which light passes to the lens and onto the retina. The brain completes the job; the result, vision. For it all to work, the cornea must be crystal clear. `` It's an amazing thing, the cornea,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Dahl </PERSON>, the lab director. `` It's the most sensitive tissue in the body, which is why the tiniest grain of sand on it will hurt. Yet it also is very resilient, and the fact that it contains no blood vessels makes it easily passed on. Rejection by the recipient is extremely rare. The success rate is better than 90 percent. `` Some recipients who received a transplant when they were young, from a middle-aged or even elderly donor, are looking through corneas perhaps 100 years old.'' Ms. <PERSON> Dahl </PERSON>'s education was in biology and chemistry, not medicine. She got her job at the eye bank through a help-wanted ad and trained on the job. She was certified by the <ORGANIZATION> Eye </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, sort of a national clearinghouse which sets the standards for technicians.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
