 EDITOR'S NOTE _ In a program that began under President <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, more than 300 White House Fellows have spent a year working in various federal departments and agencies, learning the ways of government from within. Some have stayed, and now occupy high posts in the government. Others have gone home, but with a different outlook.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the Old Executive Office Building next door to the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nuzzo </PERSON> scans column after column of numbers in a budget book and prepares a memorandum for Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. <PERSON> Nuzzo </PERSON> is a neurologist from <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. Over at the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Drysdale </PERSON> makes his way through the intricacies of farm price supports, soil conservation and consumer services. <PERSON> Drysdale </PERSON> is a venture capitalist from <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. In the office of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade representative, <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kellerhouse </PERSON> fields inquiries from mayors and governors about <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign trade policy. Ms. <PERSON> Kellerhouse </PERSON> is a financial executive on leave from the <ORGANIZATION> Port </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Nuzzo </PERSON>, <PERSON> Drysdale </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Kellerhouse </PERSON> are among a dozen Americans in their early or middle 30s who are working as White House Fellows in a program that has survived from <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Great </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> to <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s New American Revolution. Since 1965, more than 300 of them have passed through <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, spending 12 months working in federal departments and agencies to learn the ways of government. Some have stayed, and occupy high posts in the government. Others have gone home. White House Fellows work at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Arms </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disarmament </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> and in the White House. Of the current crop, one is a newspaper marketing executive, three are attorneys, one is vice president of a scientific products firm. Three are <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> majors, one a captain in the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>. During their September-through-August stint, for which they were chosen from among about 800 applicants, they receive a salary of up to $ 55,000 a year. Officials say most of them, successful in their own careers, absorb a pay cut. Anyone is eligible except federal civil servants. Some of the program's graduates have big offices in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, who worked as a fellow under then-Budget Director <PERSON> Caspar </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> in 1971-72, is now President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s national security adviser Another alumnus, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON>, is undersecretary of state for political affairs. Another, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Karnes </PERSON>, says, `` I would n't be <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> senator today if it were n't for the White House Fellows program.'' The <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> Republican is one of two who have made it to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wirth </PERSON>, a fellow in the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> in 1967-68, is a Democratic senator from <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cisneros </PERSON> of the class of 1971-72 is mayor of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Barton </PERSON>,' 81-82, is a representative from <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Garry </PERSON> <PERSON> Carruthers </PERSON>,' 74 -'75, is governor <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>,' 65-66, is publisher of the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>,' 81-82, is director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Haas </PERSON>,' 68-69, is president of <ORGANIZATION> Levi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strauss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Doris </PERSON> <PERSON> Kearns </PERSON> met <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> when she was a fellow, and became Several former fellows are generals or admirals. It all started in 1957 with <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>, then president of the <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> for the Advancement of Teaching. `` I had been doing quite a bit of reading about the founding fathers and I was struck with the fact that just about every single one of them had very early opportunity to observe government,'' <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> recalls. `` It was right across the street, so to speak, the government of their colony.'' He also found, he says, `` that the ablest kids in the country today never saw anybody governing.'' `` I wrote a memo proposing the idea of a group of <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> fellows and had the idea that it could be financed by foundations,'' he said. `` The only problem was the bill was very high and there was n't any foundation interested in it.'' Seven years later, <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> was having lunch with <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> historian, then an aide to President <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON> said <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> was concerned that too few young people were interested in government. `` Look, I've got a memo,'' says <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>, who would later become <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s secretary of health, education and welfare. <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON> showed the memo to the president and first lady <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Bird </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> and the program was launched. Today it has a budget of slightly less than $ 500,000 a year, supplemented by private funds raised by a foundation set up by former fellows. In its early years, the program was limited to applicants between the ages of 24 and 36, but the age requirement was abandoned in response to an anti-discrimination suit. All of the current fellows, however, would have qualified under the original limits.
