<TEXT>
 The youngest fellow in history, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON>, was 23 when he served in the White House Office of Cabinet Affairs. <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON> says the experience has been `` very useful and helpful'' in his present job _ vice president for current comedy programs at <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>. `` Relationships between the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the departments and agencies are much like that between a television network and the various studies and production companies,'' he says. `` The political dynamic is very similar.'' <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON> says the program needs to be better publicized. `` Everybody knows what the Rhodes scholarship is and very few people know what the White House fellowship is.'' Applications are first reviewed at a January reunion of alumni, who cut them to about 130. Those applicants are invited to travel at their own expense to 11 cities to be interviewed by panels of prominent citizens. This cuts the field to 33, who come to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> at government expense for a weekend for more interviews by members of the presidentially appointed <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on White House Fellowships. For some, like <PERSON> Karnes </PERSON>, the interview will be their first trip to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. For others, the capital is familiar ground. <PERSON> Nuzzo </PERSON>, for instance, had been a House page and attended <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Nuzzo </PERSON>, 31, said he heard about the program while in college. After completing medical school and residency, he applied so he could `` decide whether I'm going to be a practicing clinician or whether I wanted to get involved with policy full time.'' He says he reached his decision on his third day in the job: he chose a life of public service. On one recent day, <PERSON> Nuzzo </PERSON> sat in on a meeting of the subcabinet <ORGANIZATION> Interagency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> from 8:30 until sometime after 9:30 a.m., came back to the office and did some reading in the budget and the annual economic report to the president, `` sort of summarized some of the key kernels of material that were necessary from that,'' analyzed some taxation and civil rights issues and `` looked at the whole notion of banking deregulation.'' That was in the morning. In the afternoon, he had a meeting about AIDs financing. Not everybody's cup of tea, but for <PERSON> Nuzzo </PERSON> it's heady stuff. `` Here I am, I'm a doc from <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` A couple of months ago my big thing was figuring out whether I ought to give somebody a high colonic, and now I'm writing memoranda for the vice president.'' In addition to their regular duties, the fellows spend at least a day on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> following a member of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> around. `` That, from the fellows' point of view, is a real eye opener,'' says <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Lavin </PERSON>, assistant director of the program. `` I think up until then a lot of them have really believed in their government textooks on how it works.'' <PERSON> Drysdale </PERSON>, 32, a general partner in <ORGANIZATION> Hambrecht </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Quist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Venture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, for instance, was assigned to track Rep. E. -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Kika </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- de la <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` There are parts of it that are very, very different from the way decisions are made in the business world,'' <PERSON> Drysdale </PERSON> says. `` Often in business one or two people make a decision; in the political process it's much more open.'' The fellows also attend meetings, about once a week, at which big names in government and journalism speak. They also make trips abroad, which come out of the budget of the agency they work for. This year's group went to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in April. When President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> met with the fellows on Jan. 5, according to <PERSON> Nuzzo </PERSON>, he asked them, `` Please let me know what you find out.'' Although one out of three of the current fellows are from the armed services, officials deny there is any tilt in favor of the military. Whatever their background, said <PERSON> Nuzzo </PERSON>, `` There is almost a White House fellows Mafia of both old and new fellows, people from outside and inside the government who talk to each other a great deal.'' One alumnus of the program, <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Chao </PERSON>, recently named chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maritime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, came to the fellowship from a career in banking, to which she expects to return. `` Being an immigrant to this country, I was personally interested in how the government works,'' the Taiwanese native said. But she added, `` It was only through my business dealings that I began to understand that business and government really did n't understand each other.''
