<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ Before <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> surged far ahead of the pack, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> was the most talked-about non-candidate for president of this primary season. Here's a look at the statehouse record of <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>, who's keeping the door slightly ajar for another `` Mario scenario.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>, one of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s most eloquent voices, has toiled for 5 -LCB- years as chief executive of the nation's second-largest state, much of the time at the center of waxing and waning speculation about a possible run for the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> From his base in <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> has tackled national issues such as the federal deficit; international issues such as Third World debt, and the most basic issue of all _ life and death. `` We do innovation so casually that we do n't even get credit for it,'' says <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>, who with one 1984 speech became an instant national celebrity and kept people talking about him as a likely presidential candidate even while he insisted he had no intention of being one. Until recently, <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>'s avowed non-candidacy was regarded with much skepticism. Now the march toward the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> nomination by a fellow governor, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, seems to have all but obliterated lingering thoughts of a `` Mario scenario.'' Whatever <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> might have wrought as a candidate, in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> his handiwork has accumulated and is plain to see _ though not, as usual in matters political, uncontested. A list of administration accomplishments compiled in <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>'s office includes the mandatory seat belt law, the nation's first; the start of the largest tax cut in the state's history, and raising the drinking age from 18 to 21 The seat belt bill originated in the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>, and the governor at first expressed reservations about its effect on `` short people'' who might find wearing the belts uncomfortable. Reminded of this recently, <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said, `` I signed it.'' In 1984, <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> fought hard to raise the state's drinking age, but members of the state <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>'s majority, complaining of the administration's strong-arm lobbying, voted it down. It passed the following year after the federal government threatened to withhold federal highway money from any state that failed to raise its drinking age to 21. The tax cut approved last year was on the Legislature's initiative, says state Assembly Speaker <PERSON> Mel </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> Democrat After initial opposition to the tax-cut proposals, first championed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> majority, <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> came on board and signed the measure into law. In March, a television reporter noted in a broadcast the critics were saying the governor had n't come up with many new ideas. It's an accusation <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> has heard repeatedly, and it makes him bristle The official keeper of the <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> administration's scorecard, first assistant to the governor <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, sent the reporter a three-page list titled, `` Highlights of Cuomo Administration Innovations.'' Said the governor himself, when asked about initiatives: `` It would probably be difficult to find a five-year period in the history of the state where you had more innovation.'' He cited a string of them. One such was his fight for creation of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to study the national deficit, Third World debt and productivity. With a strong push from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed legislation in December creating the commission. `` The governor of a state gets an idea. The vice president does n't want it. The president does n't want it. And we get it. The president signs it. I think that was kind of innovative,'' says <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>. `` That certainly has the sound, if not'88, then 1992,'' says <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>'s chief <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION> antagonist, <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, the Republican majority leader of the state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, suggesting that <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> has his sights set on the White House. The commission, derisively labeled `` the <ORGANIZATION> Cuomo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'' by Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, this year's expected <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> presidential nominee, is composed of luminaries such as <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> financial expert <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Rohatyn </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON>. Co-chaired by former <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> and <PERSON> Republican </PERSON> <PERSON> Drew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, a former secretary of transportation, the commission will report after the November election. A real <ORGANIZATION> Cuomo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> is the governor's <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Competitiveness </ORGANIZATION>, a group of nationally known executives, labor leaders and economists brought together by the governor to study the same problems as they affect <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
