<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo, 1 graphic. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ They were early exiles of the Atomic Age, removed from their rich fishing grounds at <ORGANIZATION> Bikini </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atoll </ORGANIZATION> so the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could test its nuclear bombs. Today, 42 years later, some 1,500 Bikinians are scattered across the <LOCATION> Marshall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, living on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid and waiting for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to fulfill its promise and clean up their homeland.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIKINI ATOLL, Marshall Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Kilon </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauno </PERSON> looks out on the lagoon that once provided his people an abundant life and recalls those better days, before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> atomic bomb tests poisoned this remote, coral atoll with radiation. `` When I was here, life was great. We had fish, we had turtles, we had coconuts. We lived together and we took care of each other,'' Bauno, the ceremonial chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Bikini </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islanders </ORGANIZATION>, says through an interpreter. `` You always felt you were getting a big gift from God,'' adds <PERSON> Bauno </PERSON>, who is believed to be in his late 80s, although elderly Bikinians do n't keep track of their ages. Today, 42 years after 167 Bikinians left so their atoll could become a laboratory for the bomb tests, they see a glimmer of hope that their `` nuclear exile'' will be coming to an end. Under an out-of-court settlement to a lawsuit in 1985, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> agreed to pay for Bikini's cleanup and the eventual resettlement of the atoll. Scientists are still trying to determine how best to get rid of the lingering radiation. However, it's no longer a question of `` if'' the exiles can return home, but when. An estimated 1,500 Bikinians are scattered throughout the <LOCATION> Marshall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, living off aid from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government and longing for the day when <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> fulfills its promise. `` When we left, they promised us we would be the children of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Bauno </PERSON> says. `` The only thing we can do now is look to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and wait for them to do something.'' So far, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has spent $ 123 million on the Bikinians, including $ 95 million in trust funds to resettle, house and feed them. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> also has paid for studies of the radiation problem in the atoll, site of 23 atomic blasts between 1946 and 1958. With each passing day the elder Bikinians believe the chances of resuming their traditional way of life become slimmer. `` There are only a few elders left who know our traditional customs and it will not be long until they are gone also,'' says <PERSON> Tomaki </PERSON> <PERSON> Juda </PERSON>, mayor of <LOCATION> Kili </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, which has the largest population of Bikinians. `` We hope it will not be long before we can restore our traditions.'' The Bikinians, described in 1946 as a primitive fishing people, now enjoy a lifestyle they could n't have imagined 42 years ago. With American dollars they have bought Western-style clothes, TV sets, videotape recorders and even cars. But <PERSON> Bauno </PERSON> and his fellow elders say those comforts are only sedatives to ease the pain of their exile. Some 700 of the Bikinians now live on <LOCATION> Kili </LOCATION>, a 200-acre island 500 miles south of Bikini which was uninhabited when they arrived. Unlike Bikini, whose 23 remaining islands enclose a 240-square-mile lagoon teeming with fish, <PERSON> Kili </PERSON> is an isolated coconut island pounded by heavy surf. A $ 6 million trust fund provides each Bikinian about $ 30 a month, giving them a higher standard of living than most Marshallese. The Bikinians depend on canned meat and surplus food provided by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government to supplement the coconuts and breadfruit grown on <LOCATION> Kili </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid has provided the Bikinians plywood houses, electricity and medical care. The Bikinians also have built what local pilots call the best airstrip in the Marshalls outside of <LOCATION> Majuro </LOCATION>, the capital.
</TEXT>
