<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
<HEAD>BIKINI ATOLL, Marshall Islands: the capital.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Some people call them rich, but a <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> and a plywood house is n't rich,'' says <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Niedenthal </PERSON>, an American who is an adviser and interpreter for the Bikinians. While the Bikini elders try to keep tradition alive on <LOCATION> Kili </LOCATION>, the American influence is strong. Some of the 100 children attending <PERSON> Kili </PERSON>'s three-building school have first names such as Rambo, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Norris </PERSON>. A popular activity on <PERSON> Kili </PERSON> is to drive one of the island's 30-odd Japanese cars at midday with the air conditioner running _ an event they call `` jumbo. `` The cars are a way of taking away the burden of living on <LOCATION> Kili </LOCATION>,'' says <PERSON> Mayor </PERSON> <PERSON> Juda </PERSON>. `` Getting in a car and riding around gives you a feeling of not being so stuck, even though driving from one end of <PERSON> Kili </PERSON> to the other takes only a couple of minutes.'' Twenty police officers take turns patrolling <PERSON> Kili </PERSON>'s two miles of dirt road in a pickup truck equipped with a $ 15 dollar siren. Police hand out tickets of up to $ 25 for offenses ranging from running one of the island's dozen stop signs to exceeding the 5 mph speed limit established in the island's living area. The greatest thrill for the Bikinians is when the elders return to check the progress of work at Bikini. The latest trip was made in early April, when 50 joined <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials to mark the start of construction of a $ 30 million base camp once the method of cleaning Bikini is agreed upon. The Bikinians and their <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> attorney, <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Weisgall </PERSON>, continue to lobby the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government for money for the cleanup and resettlement, which is expected to cost between $ 120 million and $ 215 million. So far, the government has appropriated a few hundred thousand dollars to begin construction of the base camp, <PERSON> Weisgall </PERSON> says. <PERSON> Weisgall </PERSON> has proposed that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government establish another trust fund that would allow the Bikinians pay for the resettlement themselves. The plan, which <PERSON> Weisgall </PERSON> said would involve a commitment of about $ 100 million, has received support from some congressional leaders and from <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> of the Department of the Interior, the Bikini project officer. `` I think all our problems can be addressed and resolved by a trust fund,'' <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> says. `` The trust fund we think puts the responsibility on the Bikinians themselves rather than bureaucrats in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>.'' For the past 10 years, American scientists have studied the radiation problem on the main island of Bikini, whose soil is laced with radioactive cesium-137 from the explosion of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s most powerful hydrogen bomb in 1954. The researchers say it will take between five and 10 years to clean <LOCATION> Bikini </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, where most of the Bikinians will live. Scientists say that without treatment locally grown food wo n't be safe until well into the 21st century They are considering three cleanup alternatives: removing the topsoil in which the radioactive material is concentrated, treating the soil with potassium to prevent the uptake of radioactivity by plants and irrigation with sea water. For now, the Bikinians remain at the mercy of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` They give us a little money and we buy our food,'' <PERSON> Bauno </PERSON> says. `` Then we stare at them again and they give us a little more. `` That's all we can do. We just look to these Americans, saying, ` Continue helping us because we're still away from where we want to be.'''
</TEXT>
