<FIRST>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek Adv22   05-09 0865</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Theater Week, Adv 22,0890</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv22</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Clarence </PERSON> <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON> was 9 years old, he joined a gospel troupe called the Happyland Jubilee Singers. Nearly 50 years later, he is still praising the Lord in song. He and the group, now called <PERSON> Clarence </PERSON> <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON> and the Five Blind Boys of <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, are appearing in the musical `` The Gospel at Colonus.'' The show sets Sophocles' tale of Oedipus the King within the framework of a black Pentecostal church service and its rousing gospel music. `` I learned most of my gospel singing in school,'' says Fountain, sitting backstage at Broadway's Lunt-Fontanne Theater where `` Colonus'' is playing. His school, which went from grades one through 12, was the <ORGANIZATION> Talladega </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> for the Deaf and <PERSON> Blind </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Talladega </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>. Fountain, who has been blind since he was 2, sang in the school choir, but gospel music was a part of his life even before that His father was a steward in a Methodist church in <LOCATION> Selma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION> `` I was the only one in the family who sang, though,'' he says. `` It became something that grows on you.'' The Happyland Jubilee Singers continued to perform after Fountain and the other members left school early to perform during the mid-1940s. In 1947, they moved to <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, where they had a 15-minute gospel broadcast each weekday at 6:45 a.m. The name `` Five Blind Boys of <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>'' was born the following year, courtesy of a <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, promoter who began to manage the troupe. The Blind Boys would play one-night stands, all over the country, appearing in schools, churches and auditoriums. They eventually worked their way up to such places as the Apollo Theater and <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, and made a lot of records. One of their songs, `` Precious Lord, Take My Hand,'' was a best seller in 1953. `` It was a touching song,'' Fountain recalls. `` People responded.'' `` We always sang gospel,'' Fountain says. `` That was the big thing. You could n't sing rock' n' roll and then turn around and sing gospel. People would n't follow you. `` A lot of those people singing rock' n' roll, started by singing gospel in church. People like <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooke </PERSON> and <PERSON> Aretha </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>. There were a lot of them. That's why they can sing it so good.'' Today, <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON> says, there is a contemporary gospel sound, religious music that has a rock' n' roll beat. The Five Blind Boys have adapted to it. `` You have to keep up with the style,'' Fountain says. `` If you do n't keep up with the style, you're automatically behind the times.'' Fountain writes some of the group's songs with <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON>, who plays guitar for the troupe. `` Writing songs is just like writing a poem,'' Fountain says. `` As long as it rhymes and comes out right, you can take any poem and turn it into a song.'' If Fountain gets an idea for a song, he turns it over in his head, memorizes it and then tells <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> who writes it down. It was through <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> that Fountain and the Blind Boys met composer <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Telson </PERSON> and director <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Breuer </PERSON>, the creators of `` The Gospel at Colonus.'' `` They had the lyrics and the tunes but they did n't have the ingredients to go along with it,'' <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON> says. `` It's just like cookin' bread. You got the bread but you do n't have the salt, so it do n't taste like bread. We put the salt in.'' The show has played at the <ORGANIZATION> Walker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> and in 1983 at the <ORGANIZATION> Brooklyn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Music </ORGANIZATION> as well as all over <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> before tackling Broadway. `` The Gospel at Colonus'' stars actor <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> who narrates the church service, and it features several other gospel groups, such as <PERSON> J.J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Farley </PERSON> and the Soul Stirrers and the J.D. <ORGANIZATION> Steele </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Singers </ORGANIZATION>. But the Blind Boys get to sing in the evening's two show-stopping numbers, `` No Never'' and `` Lift Me Up.'' They bring down the house. `` It's easier to do than a concert,'' Fountain says. `` With a concert, you do n't rest. You have to really get down. In the musical, we get a chance to breathe a little.'' Today, <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON>, who has been married three times, makes his home in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. The rest of the <ORGANIZATION> Blind </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boys </ORGANIZATION> live all over the country, from <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. Before a concert tour starts, they all meet to rehearse their material and then hit the road. Fountain and the Rev. <PERSON> Olice </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> are the only original members of the group still performing. `` We all have good ears,'' he says. `` If it does n't sound right, we just leave it alone. We all agree on one thing. If it sounds good to us, we cut a record. `` My dream was to sing to the masses of people and when this play came along that was my dream. And it's happening just like I dreamed it would. We've come a long way. From the sticks to Broadway.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
