<FIRST>s i BC-BoatPeople-Camps Adv15   05-09 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Boat People-Camps, Adv 15,0436</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>For Vietnamese Refugees, the Wait for Resettlement Seems Endless</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Boat People, b0638</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CINTY LI</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUEN MUN CLOSED CAMP, Hong Kong (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 They are not soldiers but they live in military barracks; they are not prisoners, but guards watch over them. Soldiers and prisoners usually know when their terms are up, but the 2,000 or so Vietnamese boat people at this camp have little idea when they will find a home. They are not allowed to leave the prison-like camp in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s rural <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Territories </LOCATION>, about 500 miles northeast of the homeland they fled, until the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> arranges for their permanent resettlement elsewhere. For some refugees, the wait already has lasted a decade and the effects of lengthy confinement are reflected on their blank faces. A woman sitting on the top deck of a three-tiered bunk bed stares into space; a man stands motionless outside his barracks. Children who have known no other life run and play. For all the refugees, the matless wooden bunks are the center of their lives. Family pictures, calendars, clothes and other belongings are packed nearby. No one knows how long they will remain. Some meticulously count the days they've been here. `` Nine months and 19 days,'' said <PERSON> Pham </PERSON> <PERSON> My </PERSON> <PERSON> Linh </PERSON>, 29. `` You do n't understand what it's like in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>,'' she said in explaining why she's doing it. `` There are wars in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and all 17-year-olds have to join the army.'' She was happy this day because she had an interview with a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegation the day before, although she received no promises of going to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Another refugee, 17-year-old <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Thi </PERSON> <PERSON> Luyen </PERSON>, left <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> five years ago. Her mother and brothers had planned to leave with her but could not find space on the boat. `` I do n't know why I'm here,'' she said. `` I was only 12 -LRB- when I left -RRB-. Everybody left so I left.'' Miss <PERSON> Le </PERSON> said she is willing to return to <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> to rejoin her family but dares not ask about doing so. `` Some people have applied to go back in 1984 but were refused,'' she said. Despair also is widespread in the many other camps dotting <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. Two Vietnamese refugees recently hanged themselves, one in a <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> camp and another in <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>. One had complained of being in the camp too long and going nowhere; the other reportedly missed his family in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
