<HEAD>Ethiopia: Again Drought, Again War, Again Starvation</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fierce fighting is overwhelming foreign relief efforts in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s drought-stricken north, where more than 3 million people are threatened with starvation. The government expelled foreign aid workers and withdrew from much of the northern provinces of <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tigre </LOCATION>, where rebels are waging war against <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s Marxist-led government in <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION>. The government now forbids food distribution to the regions, leaving as many as 2 million people beyond the reach of the foreign emergency aid. A limited emergency operation continues through the government's <ORGANIZATION> Relief </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rehabilitation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and a consortium of Christian and indigenous groups organized under the Joint Relief Project After intervention by a special <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> envoy, the government allowed <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> personnel to return to the area where they coordinate the relief effort's trucking and airlift operations. But officials say that, at most, only 1.5 million people can be reached under current conditions and of that number, just 1 million now are being fed. Overall, an estimated 3.2 million people are in danger of starvation and depend on food aid following near-total crop failures last year. `` We've got a lot of people who are not going to get food,'' said <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relief </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, the primary coordinator of the Joint Relief Project's food distribution efforts. Relief officials and diplomats are expecting hungry peasants to migrate from the cut-off areas. All aid officials interviewed in <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION> said such a mass movement almost certainly would create huge hunger camps like those of <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s famine of 1984-86, when diseases caused by overcrowding and unsanitary conditions accounted for many of the estimated 1 million deaths then. This time, people arriving at food distribution centers still looked relatively healthy when the foreign aid workers were expelled, said <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, which has employed about half of the foreigners working in the northern relief effort. However, he and others said the peasants' health could deteriorate rapidly unless they get food. `` We're talking about people who ca n't wait days or weeks'til their next meal,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheek </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> charge d'affaires in <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION>. `` I think we're going to see people moving pretty soon. ... The future looks pretty grim right now.'' An added complication is the thousands of local government officials and leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Marxist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ethiopia </ORGANIZATION> who are fleeing rebel retaliation in the contested areas. They now are gathered in <LOCATION> Asmara </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION>'s capital, and in <LOCATION> Mekele </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Tigre </LOCATION>. The government's chief relief official in <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Berhanu </PERSON> <PERSON> Jembere </PERSON>, said in an interview that full relief operations would be resumed and foreign aid workers would be allowed to return to the north only after the area is `` cleansed of bandit activity.'' He could not say when that might be. Secessionist rebels in <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION> have been fighting for 27 years in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s longest civil war. In <LOCATION> Tigre </LOCATION>, guerrillas seeking greater autonomy and a say in the government took up arms in 1974. Relief officials fear the foreign aid workers were withdrawn from the northern provices to keep them from seeing what is happening in the war zone. They say the government's exemption of <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> personnel from the expulsion order weakened its argument that the foreigners were removed from <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION> and Tigre for their own safety. At best, they say, the government hopes to avoid the embarrassment of foreigners becoming war casualties or the inconvenience of dealing with relief convoys while it tries to fight the rebels. The worst case offered is that the governemnt wants to conceal a scorched-earth policy in the embattled territories, or to hide a policy of genocide by starvation. Despite the limited access, Western diplomats and relief officials said they had been able to confirm a government air strike on an important food distribution center in the Tigrean town of <LOCATION> Wukro </LOCATION>, which in recent weeks had fallen into rebel hands. These sources, citing accounts of eyewitnesses, said the bombing April 8 killed at least 50 people and wounded many more, minutes after several thousand peasants were given emergency food rations. <PERSON> Berhanu </PERSON> said he could not confirm an air attack, but added that the government's policy against the rebels would be `` an eye for an eye, if not more.'' He also said the safety of the drought-sticken peasants depended on their own patriotism. `` They are expected to join hands with the military so that the enemies can be wiped out,'' he said. `` The people themselves, I think, should decide _ and that decision is just to cleanse themselves of bandits.'' The military priorities also are impinging on relief efforts in other provinces less severely affected by the drought but still in need of aid. Relief workers in <LOCATION> Hararghe </LOCATION> province, east of <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shoa </LOCATION>, north of the capital, say some peasants have been afraid to leave their homes _ either to plow their fields or receive food rations _ for fear of being picked up by local officials and taken to the war zone. Sources say an emergency conscription is reaching into all corners of this North African nation to bring tens of thousands of able-bodied young men into military ranks to fight in the north. The military difficulties inhibit a well-prepared relief operation, in contrast to the food disaster three years ago, when foreign assistance arrived too late to save many of those who died. With the drought this time, food distribution began early, before malnourishment reached desperate levels, and enough grain was pledged to fulfill the projected need, estimated at 1.23 million metric tons by the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. But even before the expulsion of foreigners from the north and rebel offensives in March, the war already was hindering the relief effort. Rebel attacks and land mines destroyed more than 100 trucks used in the relief effort and often forced the closing of roads over which food moved. Now, hundreds of governent-controlled trucks that had been hauling relief food have been diverted to the war effort. The transportation shortage exacerbates problems at <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s two Red Sea ports, <LOCATION> Massawa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Assab </LOCATION>, where food is piling up without sufficient storage facilities, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> `` We're particularly concerned it could be diverted to the military,'' said Ambassador <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Cheek, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomat, said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would not allow its relief assistance to be administered by indigenous organizations whose operations were not subject to on-the-scene monitoring by foreign aid officials. `` We now have a war disaster imposed on a drought disaster,'' he said. `` We have yet to solve that, to figure out how, in the context of the double disaster, to perform our humanitarian function.''
</TEXT>
