<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Africa's Oldest War Fought in Obscurity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Ethiopia-Starvation, b0640</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the mean terrain of northern <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, secessionist rebels and black <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s biggest and best-armed military force are fighting one of the world's longest and most obscure wars. Every so often, the conflict pops to the world's attention, only to fade like a smothered flare. It has gained attention once again because a spate of recent rebel victories, drought and a cut-off of routes for food aid have combined to raise the threat of famine for 3.2 million people in the area. <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION>'s civil war began in 1961 against the feudal rule of Emperor <PERSON> Haile </PERSON> <PERSON> Selassie </PERSON>. Today it is against the Marxist, Soviet-backed government that ousted Selassie in 1973. The original rebel group, the <ORGANIZATION> Eritrean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- ELF -RRB-, broke up into four groups over religious and ideological differences. The largest and most powerful of the splinter groups is the Marxist but anti-Soviet <ORGANIZATION> Eritrean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> EPLF </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, with 30,000 fighters. The ELF, which is predominantly Moslem and conservative, now numbers about 5,000 fighters and has not been effective since its clash with the <ORGANIZATION> EPLF </ORGANIZATION> in 1972-74. The East and the West, particularly the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, have a stake in the outcome of the conflict because of <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s place on the strategic Horn of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Conservative Arab states like <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, fearful of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s current influence in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, openly support the <ORGANIZATION> EPLF </ORGANIZATION>, even though it is mainly Christian, because it opposes the Soviet presence in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> back the ELF. <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> generally has remained aloof from the conflict. While the Ethiopian government receives weapons from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and troops from <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, the West does not provide any similar support to the rebels. Most of their weapons and supplies are captured from the government. <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, one of the first countries to back the rebels at the start of their campaign against <PERSON> Selassie </PERSON>'s pro-Western government nearly three decades ago, now sides with the central government. <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> followed in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s path. The <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> both train the rebels. President <PERSON> Mengistu </PERSON> <PERSON> Haile </PERSON> <PERSON> Mariam </PERSON> has said his Ethiopian forces soon will launch a major offensive against the rebels. A dozen previous `` major offensives'' failed in the past. The rebels have <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION>'s rugged terrain as their chief ally and they have been able to stand off 120,000 Ethiopian soldiers, 20,000 Cubans and hundreds of Soviet advisers. The rebels main tactics are hit-and-run attacks and ambushes of government troops as they move through narrow, mountainous passes. For most of its 3,000-year history, <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION> has been coveted by foreign powers and neighbors. It is about the size of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and has mineral resources, including gold, iron and copper, none of which is exploited because of the war. Its 3.5 million people are mostly peasant farmers. <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION>'s allure is its geographical position. The province sits strategically at the crossroads of the Horn of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, commanding the gateway to the <LOCATION> Bab </LOCATION> el <ORGANIZATION> Mandab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strait </ORGANIZATION> from the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>, nowadays one of the main routes for Middle Eastern oil. It's 625-mile Red Sea coastline includes the ports of <LOCATION> Assab </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Massawa </LOCATION>. It has the only non-Arab access to the Red Sea. Without <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> would be landlocked.
</TEXT>
