<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Colors'' and ``White Mischief''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` COLORS'' `` Colors'' marks the return of <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopper </PERSON> to directing, and that should have been news in itself. His 1969 `` Easy Rider'' changed the face of the Hollywood film industry forever, then <PERSON> Hopper </PERSON> fell from grace. After two decades of drugs and booze, he turned his life around and returned as an actor of remarkable depth. Reportedly the insistence of <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> Penn </PERSON> resulted in <LOCATION> Hopper </LOCATION>'s chance to direct again A good thing. `` Colors'' reveals <PERSON> Hopper </PERSON> as a filmmaker of great skill, though a glimmer remains of the indulgences that contributed to his downfall. As a director of action, <PERSON> Hopper </PERSON> is superlative. Just when you think you had seen every kind of car chase, he provides one through the streets and back alleys of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> that is truly breathtaking. And a fugitive's rampage through a crowded restaurant, pursued by <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION>, is a kinetic wonder. On the downside, <PERSON> Hopper </PERSON> betrays his existential tendencies, staging confrontational scenes that have no real motivation or payoff. This partly may be due to <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Schiffer </PERSON>'s rather formless script. <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Duvall </PERSON> are unlikely partners on the gang war scene. <PERSON> Duvall </PERSON> is nearing retirement, a cool head who tries to establish a rapport with gang members. <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION> is hotheaded and himself prone to violence. Both try to act as <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacemakers in the growing war between the `` Bloods'' and the `` Cripps.'' `` Colors'' manages to portray the gang members as human beings not senseless criminals. <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION>, who may be the <PERSON> Brando </PERSON> of his generation, continues his string of impressive performances, and <PERSON> Duvall </PERSON> performs with his usual authority. <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Conchita </PERSON> <PERSON> Alonso </PERSON> is wasted as the obligatory love interest. The Orion release was produced by <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Solo </PERSON> and scored with fine, thumping style by <PERSON> Herbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Hancock </PERSON>. The R rating is well deserved because of the street language, violence, nudity and sex scenes. Running time: 2 hours. _ By <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` WHITE MISCHIEF'' While <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> broiled with the ravages of World War II, British colonists frolicked at <LOCATION> Happy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>. The war for them was a distant thunder: Theirs was a life of sex, drugs and endless perversions _ mirroring the downside and downfall of the British Empire. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Radford </PERSON> captures that aristocratic decadence in <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION>'s `` White Mischief,'' a <ORGANIZATION> Nelson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> and Goldcrest release, starring <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Miles </PERSON>, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Dance </PERSON> and <PERSON> Greta </PERSON> <PERSON> Scacchi </PERSON>. The arrogant and carefree Earl of <PERSON> Erroll </PERSON> -LRB- Dance -RRB- leads the pack in a round of parties, costume balls, group sex, club romps, polo matches and horse races. He has had affairs with every white woman in the area and possibly some black African women as well. Into his seedy sphere steps the ever-so-straight Sir Jock Delves <PERSON> Broughton </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Joss </PERSON> <PERSON> Ackland </PERSON> -RRB-, a reserved 57-year-old, and his sensual 27-year-old bride, <PERSON> Diana </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Scacchi </PERSON> -RRB-. With one smoldering glance, <PERSON> Erroll </PERSON> and <PERSON> Diana </PERSON> soon find their way to bed and a tumultuous affair that leads to his murder. <PERSON> Jock </PERSON> is put on trial for the homicide and acquitted. But in the aftermath, his colder, more vicious side is revealed, and the <LOCATION> Happy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> community realizes its last gasp. One would think that decadence and death would be good fodder for a fast-paced flick. But `` White Mischief'' is like a puritanical stripteaser: It promises more than it delivers. Still, there are some outstanding performances and delicious dialogue, especially from <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Miles </PERSON> as the kinky <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Janze </PERSON>. <PERSON> Alice </PERSON>, who bed hops with the best of them, is said to have murdered her first husband. During the trial reference is made to this, without naming her. Later, reporters ask <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> if she's the woman in question. Her response: `` Which one?'' The woman who killed her husband, the reporter says. `` Which one?'' she deadpans. Her straight-faced equal is <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurt </PERSON>, who has a much too small role as the rancher who also sets his sights on <PERSON> Diana </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ackland </PERSON>'s cuckolded <PERSON> Broughton </PERSON> is perfect in his restraint. Dance, however, seems almost miscast: He is not a looker nor particularly sensual. But he makes his character full of indifference with unbridled decadence, and that is the mood we are to feel throughout. There is excellent photography by <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Deakins </PERSON> of the splendid Kenyan landscape, and spritely costuming by <PERSON> Marit </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>. The <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> White-Umbrella </PERSON> Films Production runs 100 minutes and is rated R for language, drug use and adult themes. _ By <PERSON> Dolores </PERSON> <PERSON> Barclay </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Editor </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
