<HEAD>Central Bank Intervenes As Pound Rises On Lawson Resignation
Rumors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Bank of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> intervened in the foreign exchange market to stem a surge in the pound, as rumors flew Monday that Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> was planning to resign, dealers said. The intervention was light to moderate, dealers said. A Bank of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> official declined to comment on the reports of intervention. A <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> official denied the rumors about <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>. Neither official was identified, in accordance with British custom. The pound rose to $ 1.8785 by midday local time from $ 1.8730 in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> on Friday. It was quoted well above 3.1300 West German marks at 3.1587 marks. Dealers said sterling began to climb in overnight trading, in the wake of a bullish report by the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which was highlighted in The Sunday Times. In the report, <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> chief international economist <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> said the pound was significantly undervalued against the Deutsche mark and could climb over the next few months. The report contended that British industry would still be competitive if the pound rose as high as 3.27 marks. Dealers said the report served as an excuse to buy pounds. Rumors that <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> would resign sent sterling surging in the early afternoon before the intervention took place, dealers said. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> favors intervention to stem the pound's rise. When <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> stated on March 10 that any further rise in the pound's rise could not be sustained, the pound stood at 3.08 marks. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> clashed at that time with Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, who said the pound should be allowed to rise in foreign exchange markets to contain inflation. <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>'s report argued that fears that the pound's rise could lead to the devastation of British industry were totally unfounded and he said <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>'s quest for stability was ill-founded. <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> said the British economy's growth rate this year will be double <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s and that while <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has a budget surplus, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> is facing an `` exploding budget deficit'' _ higher even than <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s as a percentage of national income.'' At the same time the American economy is on course for higher inflation than <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> by the end of this year, and is saddled with huge trade and budget deficits for the forseeable future, <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> said. He said the pound could surge over the next few months, perhaps to 3.20 marks and $ 2. `` People do n't appreciate how dynamic the British economy has become,'' <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> said. He said that because of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s lack of political worries and its budget surplus, foreign investors see <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> as a more attractive country in which to invest than the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The Sunday Times said the <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> report `` contradicts a widely held view in the <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> -LRB- of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> financial district -RRB- that sterling will slide in response to a rising balance of payments deficit.'' <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> said the balance of payments deficit in prospect for this year, which he expects to be between 5 billion and 6 billion pounds _ or $ 9.35 and $ 11.22 billion _ can be readily financed without any increase in interest rates. He said <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has no fundamental balance of payments problem.
