<HEAD>Accounting Firm Pays $15 Million to Settle Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Laventhol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Horwath </ORGANIZATION> has paid $ 15 million in an out-of-court settlement of a lawsuit charging the accounting firm with racketeering. The firm made the settlement last Friday with attorneys for 2,850 investors who lost a total of more than $ 20 million in a failed tax-shelter program audited by <PERSON> Laventhol </PERSON>. The settlement must be approved by a judge in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Laventhol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> Counsel <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Augenbraun </PERSON> told The Associated Press Monday. <PERSON> Laventhol </PERSON>, based in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, is the nation's ninth-largest accounting firm. A jury found in favor of the investors in February, making <ORGANIZATION> Laventhol </ORGANIZATION> the first big accounting firm to lose a jury trial under the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act. Under the federal law, known as RICO, plaintiffs are automatically eligible for triple damages. Under the racketeering charge, <PERSON> Laventhol </PERSON> was accused of complicity in the tax-shelter scheme. The shelters were offered by Dairy World Genetics Partnerships, a series of limited partnerships, in 1970, 1980 and 1981. The settlement of the class-action suit is entirely covered by <PERSON> Laventhol </PERSON>'s liability insurance, <PERSON> Augenbraun </PERSON> said. Some attorneys believe the magnitude of the <ORGANIZATION> Laventhol </ORGANIZATION> settlement could have negative implications for the accounting profession. `` As long as the plaintiffs allege that accountants are in cahoots with the company in defrauding investors, any accounting firm can get caught up in RICO,'' <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Earle </PERSON>, former general counsel of accounting firm <ORGANIZATION> Peat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marwick </ORGANIZATION>, told the Wall Street Journal.
