<HEAD>Better Office Absorption Forecast For Next Four Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The worst is over for <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>'s ailing office market, and a long-term recovery is gaining momentum that should increase occupancy over the next four years, researchers said. Most economic indicators point to a bottoming of the market in the first half of last year, said <ORGANIZATION> Rice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> vice president <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaines </PERSON>, who oversees the organization's <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Real </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estate </ORGANIZATION> Forecasting System. `` Since then, we've had positive absorption, positive job growth and generally positive economic indices,'' <PERSON> Gaines </PERSON> said. `` We are forecasting a good year for office absorption, with just over 2 million square feet absorbed in 1988.'' By 1991 or 1992, the city should not only see marked improvements in employment, but office absorption should increase to between 3.7 million and 6 million square feet, <PERSON> Gaines </PERSON> said. If a national economic downturn occurs in late 1989 or early 1990, however, about 40 percent less space will be absorbed, <PERSON> Gaines </PERSON> said. Yet even during the recession that is predicted by Rice Center's computer models, office space absorption _ the difference between the amount of space at the beginning of a certain period and the amount at the end _ will remain positive, albeit less robust `` Assuming that no more buildings are constructed, the overall occupancy rate in 1992 is projected to be approximately 81 percent, which is halfway between the current rate of 70 percent and a ` marginally healthy' rate of 90 percent,'' <PERSON> Gaines </PERSON> said. `` For Class A office space, however, the occupancy rate is expected to be slightly above 88 percent by 1992.'' A Class A building is generally of a high-quality finish, is new or competitive with new structures, and has a excellent location. The largest office market in terms of square footage if <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>'s central business district. Rice Center forecasts an overall occupancy rate this year in the central district of 80.1 percent, with Class A buildings having more tenants and a better occupancy rate of 84 percent. By 1992, the overall occupancy rate is projected to be 88 percent, with the occupancy level of Class A space pegged at 90 percent. Rice Center's <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Real </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forecasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> was two years in the making.
