<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Top computer industry executives prefer <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> over <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> or <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> for president, according to a poll conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> Gallup </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> for <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> outdistanced <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> 80 percent to 18 percent in a one-to-one faceoff and outpolled <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> 93 percent to 4 percent, the weekly newspaper reported Monday. The poll included responses from 100 chairmen, presidents or chief executives of large computer companies. Two-hundred had been asked to participate. The results were consistent with the executives' political affiliations. <PERSON> Gallup </PERSON> said 81 percent were Republicans or leaned toward the Republican party, while 18 percent were Democrats or leaned toward the Democratic party.
