<HEAD>Trade Journal: Ford Hiring For First Time Since Early Eighties</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, Ford, which ..., with four grafs to
CORRECT number of layoffs to 69,000 sted 100,000, and to UPDATE
with comment from Ford spokesman. Picks up 6th graf pvs, William
Novotny ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which earned industry-record profits in 1987 and in the first quarter of 1988, is hiring new workers for the first time since the layoffs of the early 1980s, a trade journal reported Monday. In addition, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> is using hiring techniques learned from foreign automakers who have <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories _ methods that include intense testing, screening and interviewing, Automotive News reported. The so-called transplants _ <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> factories in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ take as many as 100,000 applications to fill 2,000 openings. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, which laid off about 69,000 workers at the beginning of the decade, has only about 2,000 remaining on indefinite layoff. The others were recalled or dropped off the recall rolls after several years. `` In recent months we have in certain locations been able to hire new people because even these 2,000 people with recall rights are limited by certain restrictions to plants in their area,'' <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Foote </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's on a small scale, just a smattering here and there,'' he said. `` It's been going on for a few months.'' The latest hiring process takes about a month, a big change from practices of the past, when a worker hired Friday was put on the assembly line Monday. New workers are put up in a hotel and given a week of orientation by the company and the union. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Novotny </PERSON>, time standards representative at <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Local </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 879 </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s Twin Cities truck plant in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, said it represents `` a totally new way of hiring.'' At the Twin Cities plant, about 50 workers will be chosen from among 2,000 applicants, <PERSON> Novotny </PERSON> said. About 150 workers already have been hired at the plant, most of whom have never worked in an auto plant, said Local 879 Chairman <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Knight </PERSON>. The new workers include former teachers and members of the military. Some of the applicants not selected were children of current workers who failed drug tests, <PERSON> Novotny </PERSON> said. Drug use is one of the biggest problems in auto plants, although few union officials want to discuss it publicly. `` That has caused some heartbreak,'' <PERSON> Novotny </PERSON> said, `` but it will make a better work place in the long run.'' In addition to Twin Cities, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> also has been hiring at its <LOCATION> Wixom </LOCATION> assembly plant, which builds the <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Town </ORGANIZATION> Car and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>, at its Climate Control Division plant in <LOCATION> Plymouth </LOCATION>, and at its Plastic Products Division plant in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION>. Those three plants are outside <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. The hiring has been prompted by new <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> contract rules that allow workers who took jobs at other plants to return to their home plants as openings occur. When they leave, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> often has to hire new workers to replace them. By comparison, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest automaker, is doing no new hiring because it still has 60,000 workers on indefinite layoff and is shrinking some of its operations. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has at least 8,000 workers on indefinite layoff.
